	  </details>
	  	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-red-800 text-lg">Explain the different stages of prenatal development.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-red-100 border-red-200">
		  <p>
			Prenatal development is a complex and dynamic process that unfolds in distinct stages, each marked by specific biological events and developmental milestones. These stages are crucial for understanding how genetic and environmental factors influence human growth before birth.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Germinal Stage (Weeks 1â€“2):</strong><br>
			This initial phase begins immediately after fertilization, when the male and female gametes unite to form a zygote. The zygote undergoes rapid mitotic division as it travels through the fallopian tube toward the uterus. By the end of the first week, it becomes a blastocyst â€” a hollow ball of cells with an inner cell mass that will eventually become the embryo. Implantation into the uterine lining occurs around day 6 or 7. During this time, the placenta starts forming, and the umbilical cord begins to develop. This stage sets the foundation for all future development but is also highly vulnerable to failure due to chromosomal abnormalities or improper implantation.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Embryonic Stage (Weeks 3â€“8):</strong><br>
			Marking the beginning of organogenesis, the embryonic stage is arguably the most critical period of prenatal development. During this time, the three primary germ layers â€” ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm â€” differentiate into all the major body systems. The nervous system begins to form with the emergence of the neural tube, which later develops into the brain and spinal cord. The heart forms and begins beating around week 5, while limb buds appear and facial structures begin to take shape. Exposure to teratogens during this stage can result in structural defects or developmental delays. By the end of week 8, the organism is now referred to as a fetus and has taken on a distinctly human appearance.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Fetal Stage (Weeks 9â€“Birth):</strong><br>
			In this final stage, the focus shifts from formation of structures to their maturation and functional development. Growth accelerates, with significant increases in size, weight, and complexity. The brain undergoes extensive development, including synaptogenesis and myelination. The respiratory system matures, allowing for potential viability outside the womb after about 24 weeks. The fetus becomes increasingly responsive to external stimuli such as sound and light, showing signs of learning and memory. Late in this stage, fat deposits increase, aiding thermoregulation and preparing the baby for life outside the womb.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Throughout these stages, maternal health, nutrition, and exposure to environmental influences play a pivotal role in shaping developmental outcomes. Understanding these phases helps in identifying risk factors, implementing timely interventions, and supporting healthy prenatal development.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>
	  
	  	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-red-800 text-lg">Explain the environmental influences during prenatal development.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-red-100 border-red-200">
		  <p>
			The prenatal environment significantly impacts fetal growth and future developmental outcomes. Several external factors influence the developing embryo and fetus.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Maternal Nutrition:</strong> Adequate intake of proteins, vitamins (especially folic acid), minerals, and calories supports healthy brain and organ development. Malnutrition increases risks of low birth weight and cognitive delays.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Prenatal Care:</strong> Regular medical check-ups help detect complications early. Conditions like gestational diabetes or hypertension can be managed with timely intervention.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Teratogens:</strong> Substances such as alcohol, drugs, tobacco, and certain medications can cause developmental anomalies. Fetal Alcohol Syndrome, for example, leads to facial deformities, intellectual disability, and behavioral issues.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Stress and Emotions:</strong> High maternal stress elevates cortisol levels, which can affect fetal brain development and increase susceptibility to anxiety and mood disorders later in life.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Environmental Toxins:</strong> Exposure to lead, radiation, or infectious diseases (e.g., rubella, toxoplasmosis) can result in serious neurological and physical impairments.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Parental and Social Support:</strong> A supportive environment reduces maternal stress and promotes healthy behaviors, indirectly benefiting prenatal development.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Overall, while genetics sets the foundation, environmental factors during pregnancy shape the trajectory of development and long-term health outcomes.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
