	<!-- Question Card: Infancy -->
	<div class="question-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-xl border border-green-200">
	  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-green-700 mb-5 flex items-center">
		<span class="mr-2">ðŸ”¹</span> INFANCY
	  </h3>

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">

		<summary class="font-medium text-green-800 text-lg">Define infancy. Discuss the characteristics and adjustments during this stage.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-green-100 border-green-200">
		  <p>
			Infancy is the earliest developmental period in human life, typically spanning from birth to around two years of age. It is a time of rapid physical, cognitive, emotional, and social growth. During this stage, infants transition from complete dependence on caregivers to increasing autonomy as they develop motor skills, language abilities, and attachment relationships.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Physical Development:</strong><br>
			Infants undergo significant physiological changes. In the first year alone, most babies triple their birth weight and grow rapidly in height. Motor development follows cephalocaudal (head-to-toe) and proximodistal (center-outward) patterns. Newborns begin with reflexive movements such as grasping and sucking, and gradually gain voluntary control over head movement, sitting, crawling, standing, and walking by the end of the second year.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Cognitive Development:</strong><br>
			According to Piagetâ€™s theory, infancy corresponds to the sensorimotor stage (birth to 2 years), during which children learn about the world primarily through sensory experiences and motor actions. Key developments include object permanence â€” the understanding that objects continue to exist even when out of sight â€” and early problem-solving abilities. Around 18 months, infants begin symbolic thinking, allowing them to mentally represent objects and use language more effectively.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Emotional and Social Development:</strong><br>
			Emotional expression begins at birth, with infants displaying basic emotions like joy, distress, and surprise. By six months, more complex emotions like fear and stranger anxiety emerge. Attachment formation is a central feature of infancy. Bowlbyâ€™s attachment theory highlights how secure attachments with primary caregivers provide a safe base for exploration and foster healthy emotional regulation later in life.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Adjustments and Challenges:</strong><br>
			Infants must adapt to various environmental transitions â€” from the womb to the outside world, from exclusive milk-based nutrition to solid foods, and from sleeping continuously to developing sleep-wake cycles. They also face challenges related to health, such as susceptibility to infections, colic, and developmental delays if deprived of stimulation or proper care.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Caregiver responsiveness plays a crucial role in facilitating these adjustments. Responsive caregiving, including consistent feeding, comforting, and interaction, supports optimal development across domains. Neglect or deprivation during infancy can have long-lasting effects on cognitive potential, emotional stability, and social functioning.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>
	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-green-800 text-lg">Elucidate the psychosocial development in infancy.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-green-100 border-green-200">
		  <p>
			Psychosocial development in infancy refers to the emotional and relational growth that occurs from birth to around two years of age. It encompasses the formation of attachment, emotional regulation, and the emergence of basic trust in the world, all of which lay the foundation for future relationships and personality development.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Attachment Formation:</strong><br>
			One of the most significant aspects of psychosocial development in infancy is the formation of attachment â€” the deep emotional bond between an infant and their primary caregiver. John Bowlby's attachment theory highlights that infants have an innate drive to form attachments as a survival mechanism. Mary Ainsworth's "Strange Situation" experiment identified four types of attachment: secure, avoidant, ambivalent, and disorganized.
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Secure Attachment:</strong> The infant explores confidently when the caregiver is present, seeks comfort upon separation, and is easily soothed upon reunion.</li>
			<li><strong>Insecure-Avoidant:</strong> The infant shows little distress when separated and avoids contact upon return.</li>
			<li><strong>Insecure-Ambivalent:</strong> The infant is overly distressed during separation and ambivalent upon reunion.</li>
			<li><strong>Insecure-Disorganized:</strong> The infant displays inconsistent behavior, often reflecting confusion or fear.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Secure attachment is fostered by consistent, responsive caregiving. Infants who receive prompt attention to their needs tend to develop a strong sense of security and trust, which enhances their ability to explore and learn.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Emotional Development:</strong><br>
			Emotions begin to appear early in infancy. Newborns show signs of distress, interest, and pleasure. By 2â€“3 months, infants smile socially and express joy. Around 6â€“8 months, stranger anxiety and separation protest emerge, indicating growing awareness of familiar versus unfamiliar people.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			By the end of the first year, infants can express more complex emotions such as pride, shame, and empathy. Emotional regulation begins to develop as infants learn to soothe themselves or seek comfort from caregivers. Over time, they become more capable of modulating emotional responses through learned behaviors and environmental cues.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Temperament:</strong><br>
			Temperament plays a key role in how infants respond emotionally and behaviorally to their environment. Thomas and Chess identified nine dimensions of temperament, including activity level, rhythmicity, approach/withdrawal, and adaptability. Based on these, they categorized infants into three temperamental types: easy, difficult, and slow-to-warm-up.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			A child's temperament interacts with parenting style to shape psychosocial outcomes. For instance, a difficult temperament combined with unresponsive caregiving may lead to behavioral problems, whereas supportive caregiving can buffer against negative outcomes.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Development of Trust vs Mistrust (Erikson):</strong><br>
			Erik Erikson's first psychosocial stage â€” <strong>trust vs mistrust</strong> â€” occurs during infancy (birth to 18 months). If infantsâ€™ needs are consistently met, they develop a sense of trust in the world and feel safe exploring it. Conversely, inconsistent or neglectful care may lead to mistrust, making the infant wary and anxious.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			This foundational stage influences all subsequent stages of psychosocial development. Infants who experience warm, reliable care are more likely to progress successfully through later stages involving autonomy, initiative, and identity.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In conclusion, psychosocial development in infancy is a multifaceted process involving attachment, emotional regulation, temperament, and early personality formation. Responsive caregiving and a nurturing environment are crucial for fostering healthy psychosocial growth during this sensitive period.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
