	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-teal-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-teal-800 text-lg">Attachment Patterns.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-teal-100 border-teal-200">
		  <p>
			Attachment patterns describe how infants form emotional bonds with caregivers. Mary Ainsworth identified four types via the Strange Situation:
		  </p>
		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-2">
			<li><strong>Secure:</strong> Seeks comfort and explores confidently</li>
			<li><strong>Insecure-Avoidant:</strong> Avoids caregiver upon reunion</li>
			<li><strong>Insecure-Ambivalent:</strong> Clings and shows mixed emotions</li>
			<li><strong>Insecure-Disorganized:</strong> Shows inconsistent behavior, often due to trauma or inconsistency</li>
		  </ul>
		  <p>
			Secure attachment is linked to responsive caregiving and predicts better emotional regulation and relationship quality later in life.
		  </p>
		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>
	  
	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-indigo-800 text-lg">Describe the physical and psychological development during infancy.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-indigo-100 border-indigo-200">
		  <p>
			Infancy spans from birth to approximately two years of age and is marked by rapid and profound changes across physical, sensory, cognitive, and emotional domains. Both physical and psychological development during this stage are interdependent and lay the foundation for future growth and learning.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Physical Development:</strong><br>
			Physical development in infancy involves growth in size, refinement of motor skills, and maturation of bodily systems.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Growth Patterns:</strong><br>
			Infants grow rapidly during the first year. On average, babies double their birth weight by six months and triple it by one year. Height increases by about 10 inches in the first year. Growth slows slightly in the second year, but continues steadily.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Brain Development:</strong><br>
			The brain undergoes dramatic growth during infancy. Synaptogenesis (formation of neural connections) peaks in the first two years, particularly in areas related to language, memory, and emotion. Myelination â€” the development of protective sheaths around neurons â€” enhances the speed and efficiency of neural transmission.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Motor Development:</strong><br>
			Motor development follows predictable sequences:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Gross Motor:</strong> Head control â†’ Rolling â†’ Sitting â†’ Crawling â†’ Standing â†’ Walking</li>
			<li><strong>Fine Motor:</strong> Grasping reflex â†’ Raking grasp â†’ Pincer grasp â†’ Scribbling â†’ Using utensils</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			These milestones reflect increasing neuromuscular control and coordination. Environmental stimulation and opportunities for movement play a vital role in motor development.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Sensory Development:</strong><br>
			Vision and hearing improve dramatically. Newborns see only blurry images and prefer high-contrast patterns. By 6 months, visual acuity approaches adult levels. Hearing is well-developed at birth, and infants begin distinguishing speech sounds relevant to their native language by 6â€“8 months.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Psychological Development:</strong><br>
			Psychological development during infancy includes emotional, social, and cognitive growth.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Emotional Development:</strong><br>
			Infants begin expressing basic emotions like happiness, sadness, surprise, and disgust within the first few months. By 6â€“8 months, more complex emotions such as fear (stranger anxiety) and wariness appear. Emotional regulation develops gradually, supported by caregiver responsiveness and modeling.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Social Development:</strong><br>
			Social bonding begins immediately after birth through eye contact, touch, and voice. Attachment forms primarily with caregivers, typically peaking between 6â€“12 months. Secure attachment provides a base for exploration and fosters resilience and confidence.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Cognitive Development (Piaget):</strong><br>
			According to Jean Piaget, infancy corresponds to the sensorimotor stage (birth to 2 years), during which knowledge is gained through sensory experiences and motor actions. Key developments include object permanence (understanding that objects exist even when out of sight) and early problem-solving abilities.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Language Development:</strong><br>
			Infants progress from cooing and babbling to producing meaningful words by the end of the first year. Receptive language (understanding) precedes expressive language (speaking). By age 2, many children can combine words into simple sentences.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Overall, infancy is a period of rapid transformation in every domain of development. Physical and psychological growth is closely intertwined, and the quality of caregiving and environmental stimulation significantly influences developmental outcomes.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>
	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-purple-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-purple-800 text-lg">Explain linguistic development during infancy.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-purple-100 border-purple-200">
		  <p>
			Linguistic development during infancy begins shortly after birth and progresses through distinct stages. Though infants cannot speak initially, they are biologically equipped to perceive and produce speech sounds, laying the groundwork for language acquisition.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Pre-Linguistic Communication (0â€“12 months):</strong><br>
			From birth, infants communicate through crying, cooing, and babbling. Crying is the first form of communication, signaling hunger, discomfort, or distress. Around 2â€“4 months, infants begin cooing â€” producing vowel-like sounds. By 6â€“9 months, babbling emerges, including repetitive consonant-vowel combinations (e.g., "ba-ba," "da-da").
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Phonological Awareness:</strong><br>
			Infants become increasingly sensitive to the sounds of their native language. By 6â€“8 months, they distinguish speech sounds (phonemes) relevant to their language and begin ignoring non-native contrasts. This is known as perceptual narrowing.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Semantic Development:</strong><br>
			Between 9â€“12 months, infants begin to associate sounds with meanings. First words usually appear around 12 months, often including names, familiar objects, or common phrases (e.g., "mama," "dada," "no").
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Syntactic and Grammatical Development:</strong><br>
			By 18â€“24 months, infants begin combining words into two-word utterances (telegraphic speech). These early sentences follow grammatical rules, such as "more juice" or "go park." Despite being brief, they convey meaning and intent.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Pragmatic Development:</strong><br>
			Infants also learn how to use language socially. They engage in joint attention, point to objects, take turns in conversations, and respond to adult speech. These interactions lay the foundation for effective communication and social interaction.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Environmental Influences:</strong><br>
			Linguistic development is strongly influenced by caregiver interaction. Responsive adults who talk frequently, name objects, and engage in back-and-forth exchanges foster faster language growth. Exposure to rich, varied input encourages vocabulary expansion and syntactic complexity.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Neurological Foundations:</strong><br>
			Brain regions such as Brocaâ€™s area and Wernickeâ€™s area become active early in life, supporting speech production and comprehension. Myelination and synaptogenesis during the first two years support rapid language acquisition.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In summary, linguistic development during infancy is a gradual but dynamic process involving perception, production, comprehension, and social use of language. With consistent input and interaction, infants steadily progress from babbling to meaningful speech.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
