	<!-- Question Card: Early Childhood (0â€“6 years) -->
	<div class="question-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-xl border border-cyan-200">
	  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-cyan-700 mb-5 flex items-center">
		<span class="mr-2">ðŸ”¹</span> EARLY CHILDHOOD (0-6 Years)
	  </h3>

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-blue-800 text-lg">Describe social development during early childhood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-blue-100 border-blue-200">
		  <p>
			Social development during early childhood (ages 2â€“6) refers to the process through which children learn to interact with others, understand social norms, regulate emotions, and develop a sense of self within a social context. This stage is foundational for building relationships, communication skills, empathy, and moral understanding.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Emergence of Self-Awareness:</strong><br>
			Around age 2, children begin to recognize themselves as distinct individuals. This self-awareness develops gradually through interactions with caregivers and peers. By age 3â€“4, children can identify themselves in mirrors, express preferences, and use personal pronouns like "I" and "me." As they grow, they start forming a more complex self-concept based on roles (e.g., sibling, student), traits (e.g., shy, outgoing), and values.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Peer Relationships:</strong><br>
			During early childhood, peer interaction becomes increasingly important. Initially, play is parallel â€” children playing side by side but not together. By age 4 or 5, cooperative play emerges, where children engage in shared activities, take turns, and negotiate roles. These interactions help them learn conflict resolution, perspective-taking, and cooperation â€” essential skills for later life.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Social Learning and Imitation:</strong><br>
			Children at this stage are highly observant and imitate behaviors modeled by parents, siblings, teachers, and media figures. Albert Banduraâ€™s social learning theory emphasizes how children acquire social behaviors such as aggression, politeness, and altruism through observation and imitation. Positive reinforcement encourages prosocial behavior, while negative consequences may discourage antisocial actions.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Moral Development:</strong><br>
			According to Piaget, young children initially follow a heteronomous morality â€” believing rules are fixed and must be obeyed. They judge actions based on consequences rather than intentions. As cognitive abilities mature, they transition toward autonomous morality, recognizing that rules can be negotiated and intentions matter more than outcomes. Kohlberg expanded on this, identifying stages of moral reasoning that begin with obedience and evolve into principled thinking.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Emotional Regulation:</strong><br>
			Emotional regulation improves significantly during early childhood. Young children often display intense emotions, but over time, they learn strategies to manage frustration, fear, and anger. Caregivers play a crucial role in modeling emotional control and teaching verbal expression of feelings instead of tantrums or aggression.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Gender Identity and Role Development:</strong><br>
			Children also begin to internalize gender roles based on cultural expectations and parental modeling. By age 3, most children can identify their gender; by 5 or 6, they understand that gender remains constant over time (gender constancy). Gender-typed behaviors emerge as children adopt roles associated with their gender, influenced by both biological factors and socialization.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In summary, early childhood is a dynamic period of social growth. Through family, peers, school, and media, children build the foundation for lifelong interpersonal skills, ethical behavior, and emotional intelligence.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>
	
	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-red-800 text-lg">Explain motor development during early childhood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-red-100 border-red-200">
		  <p>
			Motor development refers to the progression of physical skills involving body movement and coordination. In early childhood (ages 2â€“6), motor development is divided into two main categories: gross motor skills and fine motor skills. These skills are essential for daily functioning, exploration, and learning.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Gross Motor Skills:</strong><br>
			Gross motor skills involve large muscle groups used for activities such as walking, running, jumping, climbing, balancing, and throwing. At age 2, children walk independently and climb stairs with support. By age 3, they can run more steadily, kick a ball, and pedal a tricycle. At 4â€“5 years, they gain better balance and coordination, allowing them to hop on one foot, jump rope, and navigate playground equipment. These skills improve due to brain maturation, increased muscle strength, and practice.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Fine Motor Skills:</strong><br>
			Fine motor skills involve smaller muscle movements, especially in the hands and fingers, and are critical for tasks like drawing, writing, cutting with scissors, and manipulating small objects. At age 2, children grasp crayons awkwardly and stack blocks. By age 3, they can scribble purposefully and turn pages one at a time. At age 4â€“5, they refine hand-eye coordination and dexterity, enabling them to draw recognizable shapes, use utensils effectively, and begin writing letters.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Factors Influencing Motor Development:</strong><br>
			Several factors influence the pace and quality of motor development:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Biological Maturation:</strong> Neural development, myelination of nerve fibers, and muscular growth underpin improved coordination and speed.</li>
			<li><strong>Practice and Experience:</strong> Regular opportunities to move, explore, and manipulate objects enhance skill acquisition.</li>
			<li><strong>Nutrition:</strong> Adequate intake of protein, vitamins, and minerals supports muscle and nervous system development.</li>
			<li><strong>Environmental Stimulation:</strong> Playgrounds, toys, and structured activities encourage motor challenges and learning.</li>
			<li><strong>Caregiver Support:</strong> Encouragement, modeling, and assistance foster confidence and persistence.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Developmental Milestones:</strong><br>
			Typical milestones include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Age 2: Walks up stairs holding rail, kicks a ball forward</li>
			<li>Age 3: Climbs furniture, throws ball overhead</li>
			<li>Age 4: Hops on one foot, catches large ball</li>
			<li>Age 5: Skips, rides a bike with training wheels, uses scissors</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Delays in motor development can indicate underlying neurological, muscular, or developmental disorders and should be evaluated early. However, most children develop motor skills progressively and adaptively, laying the groundwork for academic readiness and social participation.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-red-800 text-lg">Psychological hazards during early childhood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-red-100 border-red-200">
		  <p>
			Early childhood (ages 2â€“6) is a critical developmental window. However, it is also a vulnerable time during which psychological hazards can have lasting effects if not addressed early.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Neglect and Emotional Deprivation:</strong><br>
			Children who receive minimal attention, affection, or emotional support may develop attachment issues, low self-esteem, and difficulties in forming relationships later in life.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Trauma and Abuse:</strong><br>
			Exposure to abuse â€” physical, emotional, or sexual â€” can lead to trauma responses, behavioral problems, aggression, withdrawal, or developmental regression.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Parental Conflict and Divorce:</strong><br>
			High levels of parental conflict or divorce can create instability and confusion. Young children may internalize blame, show regressive behavior, or become emotionally withdrawn.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Overprotection or Authoritarian Parenting:</strong><br>
			Excessive control or lack of autonomy can hinder initiative-taking and decision-making abilities. Children may become overly dependent or anxious.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Frequent Changes in Caregivers:</strong><br>
			Consistent caregiving is essential for attachment formation. Frequent changes in caregivers or moving between homes can disrupt emotional stability and trust.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>6. Health Issues:</strong><br>
			Chronic illness, hospitalization, or disability can affect how children perceive themselves and interact with others. They may struggle with identity or feelings of inadequacy.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>7. Peer Rejection:</strong><br>
			While peer interaction becomes more common in this stage, rejection or bullying can trigger social anxiety, low self-worth, and isolation.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>8. Unrealistic Expectations:</strong><br>
			Pressures to perform academically or socially beyond developmental readiness can cause stress, frustration, and lowered motivation.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Supportive Strategies:</strong><br>
			- Providing stable, nurturing environments<br>
			- Encouraging exploration and play<br>
			- Modeling emotional regulation<br>
			- Ensuring consistency in care and expectations<br>
			- Seeking professional help when behavioral or emotional issues persist
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In summary, while early childhood is a time of remarkable growth, it is also a sensitive period for psychological hazards. Recognizing and addressing these risks early helps foster emotional resilience and healthy development.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
