	<!-- Question Card: Middle Childhood (6â€“11 years) -->
	<div class="question-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-xl border border-green-200">
	  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-green-700 mb-5 flex items-center">
		<span class="mr-2">ðŸ”¹</span>Middle Childhood (6â€“11 years)
	  </h3>

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-purple-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-purple-800 text-lg">Discuss social development during middle childhood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-purple-100 border-purple-200">
		  <p>
			Middle childhood (ages 6â€“12) is a critical time for social development. As children enter school and expand their social circles, they learn to navigate complex social dynamics, manage conflicts, and build meaningful relationships.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Peer Group Integration:</strong><br>
			Children begin to identify with peer groups and form friendships based on shared interests. Acceptance and belonging become important motivators.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Cooperative Play:</strong><br>
			Unlike early childhood, middle childhood sees increased cooperation, team participation, and rule-based games. Children understand fairness and reciprocity better.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Social Comparison:</strong><br>
			At this stage, children compare themselves to peers academically, physically, and socially. This can influence self-esteem â€” both positively and negatively.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Group Norms and Conformity:</strong><br>
			Children begin to adopt group norms regarding fashion, behavior, and attitudes. Peer pressure starts to shape choices, though it intensifies further in adolescence.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Moral Reasoning:</strong><br>
			Children become more aware of right and wrong. They understand that intentions matter more than outcomes, reflecting Kohlbergâ€™s preconventional morality.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>6. Conflict Resolution:</strong><br>
			Disputes over toys, grades, or friendship alliances teach children to resolve conflicts verbally rather than physically. They learn negotiation, apologies, and compromise.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>7. Social Roles and Responsibilities:</strong><br>
			Children take on roles like leader, follower, or mediator. They also begin to understand responsibilities in group settings (e.g., classroom duties).
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>8. Sense of Belonging:</strong><br>
			Being part of clubs, teams, or school activities enhances a child's sense of community and purpose. Feeling excluded can lead to loneliness or low motivation.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>9. Respect for Diversity:</strong><br>
			Exposure to diverse peers fosters tolerance and reduces prejudice. Children learn to appreciate differences in culture, ability, and background.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>10. Teacher Influence:</strong><br>
			Teachers serve as authority figures and mentors. Their feedback influences how children see themselves socially and academically.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In summary, social development in middle childhood prepares children for adolescence and adulthood. It builds skills in cooperation, conflict management, and identity within a group. Supporting this growth through inclusive practices and constructive feedback is vital.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
