	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-yellow-800 text-lg">Developing math skills as a basic school skill.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-yellow-100 border-yellow-200">
		  <p>
			Math skills are among the most fundamental academic abilities children develop during their early school years. These skills form the basis for logical reasoning, problem-solving, and analytical thinking.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Number Sense:</strong><br>
			Young learners begin by recognizing numbers and counting. As they progress, they understand number relationships, magnitude, and sequencing. Concepts such as greater than/less than, odd/even, and place value are introduced gradually.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Arithmetic:</strong><br>
			Children are introduced to addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division. Initially, they rely on concrete manipulatives and visual aids. Over time, they internalize procedures and begin performing mental calculations.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Problem Solving:</strong><br>
			Math education moves beyond rote computation to include word problems and real-world applications. Children learn to:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Read and interpret problems</li>
			<li>Identify relevant information</li>
			<li>Select appropriate operations</li>
			<li>Check for reasonableness of solutions</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Measurement and Geometry:</strong><br>
			Students learn to measure length, weight, volume, and time. They also explore geometric shapes, symmetry, and spatial relationships. These skills enhance their ability to describe and interact with the physical world.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Data Handling:</strong><br>
			Children learn to collect, organize, and interpret data using graphs, charts, and tables. This builds analytical thinking and prepares students for more complex statistical concepts later.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Instructional Strategies:</strong><br>
			Effective math instruction includes:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Hands-on learning with manipulatives</li>
			<li>Visual representations (number lines, bar models)</li>
			<li>Real-life applications (shopping, cooking, measuring)</li>
			<li>Games and interactive tools</li>
			<li>Structured practice and review</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Consistent exposure, scaffolded instruction, and meaningful practice help children develop confidence and competence in mathematics, setting the stage for future academic success.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
