	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-green-800 text-lg">Examine the role of peer group on social development during school years.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-green-100 border-green-200">
		  <p>
			The peer group plays a central role in shaping a childâ€™s social development during the school years. As children spend more time away from home and engage in group settings, they learn to navigate interpersonal dynamics, form friendships, and build social competence.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Social Learning:</strong><br>
			Peer groups provide opportunities to learn cooperation, communication, sharing, and empathy. Through interactions, children observe and imitate behaviors such as turn-taking, fairness, and negotiation.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Identity Formation:</strong><br>
			During middle childhood, children begin developing a sense of self in relation to peers. They explore roles, compare themselves with others, and seek acceptance based on shared interests, values, and appearance.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Norms and Conformity:</strong><br>
			Peers establish unspoken rules about dress, speech, and behavior. Children often adopt these norms to fit in, though excessive conformity may suppress individuality.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Emotional Support:</strong><br>
			Peer relationships offer companionship, validation, and emotional backing. Children confide in friends and seek comfort during stressful times.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Conflict Resolution:</strong><br>
			Peer groups expose children to disagreements, jealousy, and power struggles. Navigating these teaches problem-solving, compromise, and perspective-taking.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>6. Moral Development:</strong><br>
			Peer discussions and group activities influence moral reasoning. Children learn justice, fairness, and reciprocity through cooperative games and classroom projects.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>7. Influence on Academic Behavior:</strong><br>
			Peers can either motivate academic engagement or encourage disengagement depending on the groupâ€™s attitude toward school. Positive peer modeling supports study habits and learning.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>8. Risk of Bullying and Exclusion:</strong><br>
			Not all peer interactions are positive. Bullying, exclusion, or negative social comparison can harm self-esteem and lead to anxiety or depression.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Conclusion:</strong><br>
			The peer group is a powerful agent of social development during school years. It influences personality, behavior, and worldview. Educators and parents should guide children in selecting healthy peer associations and managing group dynamics constructively.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
