	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-green-800 text-lg">Compare Piaget's and Kohlberg's theories of moral development during school years.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-green-100 border-green-200">
		  <p>
			During the school years (ages 6â€“12), children move from rigid rule-following to more nuanced understandings of right and wrong. Piaget and Kohlberg offer complementary but distinct views of this moral evolution.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Piagetâ€™s View:</strong><br>
			Piaget proposed that moral development begins with <strong>heteronomous morality</strong>, where children believe rules are absolute and must be obeyed. They judge actions based on consequences â€” e.g., breaking more cups is worse than breaking fewer, regardless of intent.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Around age 8â€“10, children enter the <strong>autonomous morality</strong> stage. Here, they recognize that rules can be changed by mutual agreement and consider intentions and context in moral judgments.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Piaget emphasized the role of peer interaction in developing mature moral reasoning. Unlike adults, peers allow children to negotiate rules and understand othersâ€™ perspectives.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Kohlbergâ€™s View:</strong><br>
			Kohlberg built upon Piagetâ€™s foundation but extended moral development into adolescence and beyond. For school-age children, he identified the following relevant stages:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Stage 1:</strong> Punishment and obedience orientation</li>
			<li><strong>Stage 2:</strong> Instrumental relativist orientation</li>
			<li><strong>Stage 3:</strong> â€œGood boy/good girlâ€ orientation</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			At Stage 1, children follow rules to avoid punishment. At Stage 2, they begin to see rules as flexible tools for personal gain. By Stage 3, children value social harmony and seek approval by conforming to prosocial roles.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Similarities:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Both use staged models of moral development</li>
			<li>Both emphasize cognitive growth as a prerequisite for advanced moral reasoning</li>
			<li>Both acknowledge the importance of peer interaction in shaping moral judgment</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Differences:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Piaget focused on early childhood, while Kohlberg extended moral development into adulthood</li>
			<li>Piaget concentrated on intention versus consequence; Kohlberg included broader themes like justice and social contracts</li>
			<li>Kohlberg's approach is more structured and hierarchical; Piagetâ€™s is more descriptive and observational</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Educational Relevance:</strong><br>
			Understanding both theories helps educators design curricula and classroom practices that foster moral reasoning. Teachers can encourage cooperative learning, promote empathy, and present moral dilemmas to stimulate deeper thinking.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			While Piaget offers insight into how children think about fairness and rules, Kohlberg provides a broader roadmap of moral growth that extends beyond childhood.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
