	<!-- Question Card: Adolescence (10-19 years) -->
	<div class="question-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-xl border border-indigo-200">
	  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-indigo-700 mb-5 flex items-center">
		<span class="mr-2">ðŸ”¹</span> Adolescence (10-19 years)
	  </h3>	


	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-pink-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-pink-800 text-lg">Discuss school performance and cognitive development during adolescence.</summary>
		<div class2="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-pink-100 border-pink-200">
		  <p>
			Adolescence is a critical period for both cognitive growth and academic performance. As teens enter formal operational thinking (Piaget), they become capable of abstract reasoning, hypothetical thinking, and metacognition.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Cognitive Milestones:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Ability to think about possibilities and consequences</li>
			<li>Improved working memory and analytical skills</li>
			<li>Greater capacity for planning, organizing, and self-assessment</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			These developments enable adolescents to handle complex subjects like algebra, philosophy, and science.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>School Performance:</strong><br>
			Cognitive advances directly impact learning. Teens with strong reasoning and problem-solving skills perform better academically, especially in standardized tests and open-ended questions.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			However, school performance is also influenced by emotional maturity, motivation, peer pressure, and family support.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Factors Influencing Both:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Family Support:</strong> Encouragement enhances academic engagement and critical thinking.</li>
			<li><strong>Quality Teaching:</strong> Engaging instruction and feedback boost cognitive growth and performance.</li>
			<li><strong>Self-Efficacy:</strong> Belief in one's ability to succeed predicts academic achievement and resilience.</li>
			<li><strong>Mental Health:</strong> Anxiety, depression, and stress can interfere with both cognition and school outcomes.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			In summary, adolescence marks a peak in cognitive potential. Supporting this growth through quality education and emotional support ensures optimal school performance and lifelong learning readiness.
		  </p>

