	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-indigo-800 text-lg">Explain cognitive development during adolescence.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-indigo-100 border-indigo-200">
		  <p>
			Cognitive development during adolescence marks a dramatic leap in mental abilities. According to Jean Piaget, adolescents transition from concrete operational thought to formal operational thought, enabling them to reason abstractly, think hypothetically, and engage in metacognition â€” thinking about thinking.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Formal Operational Thought:</strong><br>
			This is the final stage of Piagetâ€™s cognitive development theory (typically emerging around age 11â€“15). It allows adolescents to:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Think abstractly about concepts like freedom, justice, and truth</li>
			<li>Engage in hypothetical-deductive reasoning</li>
			<li>Consider multiple possibilities before making decisions</li>
			<li>Develop a sense of idealism and philosophical inquiry</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			This newfound ability often leads to increased questioning of authority, exploration of identity, and interest in moral and political issues.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Metacognition:</strong><br>
			Adolescents also develop metacognitive skills â€” the ability to monitor and regulate their own thinking processes. This leads to improved planning, self-awareness, and strategic learning.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Students become better at setting goals, evaluating their progress, and adjusting strategies accordingly. This supports academic success and independent learning.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Executive Functioning:</strong><br>
			Executive functions such as working memory, attention control, and inhibitory control continue to mature during adolescence. These higher-order cognitive skills are essential for:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Planning and organizing tasks</li>
			<li>Resisting impulses and distractions</li>
			<li>Making reasoned decisions</li>
			<li>Managing time and resources effectively</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Information Processing Approach:</strong><br>
			From an information processing perspective, adolescence sees improvements in speed, accuracy, and efficiency of cognitive operations. Adolescents become faster at retrieving information, better at multitasking, and more adept at using mnemonic strategies.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Social and Emotional Context:</strong><br>
			Cognitive growth doesnâ€™t occur in isolation. As adolescents develop logical reasoning, they also grapple with emotions, peer pressure, and identity formation. This interplay influences decision-making and risk assessment.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			While cognitive capacities expand rapidly, emotional regulation lags behind, leading to inconsistencies in behavior â€” a phenomenon known as the dual systems theory (cognitive vs emotional systems).
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Educational Implications:</strong><br>
			To support cognitive development during adolescence, schools should:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Incorporate open-ended questions and debates</li>
			<li>Encourage critical thinking and hypothesis testing</li>
			<li>Provide opportunities for goal-setting and self-assessment</li>
			<li>Teach decision-making strategies and problem-solving techniques</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			In summary, adolescence is a time of profound cognitive change. With proper guidance, teens can harness these new abilities to become thoughtful, reflective, and socially responsible adults.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
