	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-gray-800 text-lg">Describe the various challenges of adolescence.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-gray-100 border-gray-200">
		  <p>
			Adolescence is a transformative developmental stage filled with numerous psychological, social, and physiological challenges. These challenges arise from rapid physical changes, evolving cognitive abilities, and shifting social roles.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Physical Changes:</strong><br>
			Puberty brings significant bodily transformations â€” height spurt, facial/body hair, voice deepening, and sexual maturation. These changes can cause embarrassment, insecurity, and self-consciousness, especially when development is earlier or later than peers.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Body image issues and eating disorders may emerge, particularly in girls. Boys may feel pressure to conform to traditional masculine ideals of strength and dominance.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Emotional Volatility:</strong><br>
			Hormonal fluctuations and brain development contribute to mood swings, impulsivity, and heightened emotional responses. Teens may experience sudden sadness, anger, or euphoria, which can strain relationships and lead to misunderstandings.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Emotional regulation skills are still developing, making it hard for adolescents to manage stress, disappointment, or rejection in a mature way.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Identity Formation:</strong><br>
			Adolescents face the task of defining who they are â€” their values, goals, beliefs, and future roles. This involves trial and error, which can lead to confusion, rebellion, or conformity.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Teens may struggle with:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Conflict between personal desires and family expectations</li>
			<li>Uncertainty about sexual orientation or gender identity</li>
			<li>Pressure to choose a career or educational path</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Peer Pressure:</strong><br>
			Peer influence peaks during adolescence. Teens may feel compelled to conform to group norms, even if they conflict with personal values. This can lead to:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Substance use</li>
			<li>Early sexual activity</li>
			<li>Bullying or victimization</li>
			<li>Conformity to fashion, slang, or lifestyle trends</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Academic and Future Pressures:</strong><br>
			School demands, college entrance exams, and career planning create immense stress. Fear of failure, competition, and performance anxiety are common.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Academic underperformance or mismatch between ability and expectation can lower self-esteem and impact motivation.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>6. Mental Health Struggles:</strong><br>
			Depression, anxiety, and self-harm rates rise during adolescence. Risk factors include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Family history of mental illness</li>
			<li>History of trauma or abuse</li>
			<li>Chronic stress or bullying</li>
			<li>Lack of emotional support</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>7. Digital and Social Media Influence:</strong><br>
			Constant connectivity can amplify comparisons, cyberbullying, and FOMO (fear of missing out). Teens may equate online popularity with personal worth, affecting self-esteem and social behavior.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Despite these challenges, adolescence is also a time of great potential. With proper guidance, adolescents can navigate this phase successfully and emerge with a stronger sense of self, improved coping skills, and readiness for adulthood.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
