	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-green-800 text-lg">Discuss James Marcia's model of identity status.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-green-100 border-green-200">
		  <p>
			James Marcia built upon Erik Eriksonâ€™s concept of identity formation to create a more nuanced understanding of adolescent and young adult development. Erikson introduced the idea of an "identity crisis" â€” a period of exploration and commitment regarding life choices. Marcia operationalized this by identifying four identity statuses based on two dimensions:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Exploration:</strong> Has the person actively explored alternatives?</li>
			<li><strong>Commitment:</strong> Has the person made firm commitments in areas like career, religion, politics, or relationships?</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Based on these criteria, Marcia identified four identity statuses:
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Identity Diffusion:</strong><br>
			  No exploration and no commitment. Common in early adolescence or those facing confusion and instability.</li>

			<li><strong>Foreclosure:</strong><br>
			  Commitment without exploration. Often due to accepting parental or societal roles without questioning.</li>

			<li><strong>Moratorium:</strong><br>
			  Active exploration without firm commitment. Teens may try different identities, beliefs, or lifestyles.</li>

			<li><strong>Identity Achievement:</strong><br>
			  Exploration followed by commitment. Reflects mature identity formation where individuals have examined options and made conscious choices.</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			<strong>Application in Education and Counseling:</strong><br>
			Marciaâ€™s model helps educators and counselors assess where adolescents stand in their identity journey:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Diffused:</strong> May require guidance to explore interests and goals</li>
			<li><strong>Foreclosed:</strong> Might benefit from exposure to alternative viewpoints</li>
			<li><strong>Moratorium:</strong> Is in a healthy phase of exploration but may need support and structure</li>
			<li><strong>Achievement:</strong> Indicates a well-developed sense of self and purpose</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			The model also applies beyond adolescence. Adults undergoing career changes, parenting challenges, or spiritual transitions may revisit earlier identity statuses before recommitting to new paths.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Example Scenarios:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>A teen who joins a political party because their parents did â€” Foreclosure</li>
			<li>An 18-year-old exploring college majors and ideologies â€” Moratorium</li>
			<li>A young adult who chooses a career after internships and volunteer work â€” Achievement</li>
			<li>A student who avoids thinking about future plans â€” Diffusion</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Conclusion:</strong><br>
			James Marciaâ€™s model provides a practical way to assess identity development. It highlights that identity is not simply adopted or discovered, but formed through active exploration and meaningful commitment.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Understanding identity status helps teachers, parents, and therapists guide individuals toward a coherent and satisfying sense of self.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
