	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-blue-800 text-lg">Comment on identity crisis in adolescence. How can it be resolved?</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-blue-100 border-blue-200">
		  <p>
			Identity crisis is a term coined by psychologist Erik Erikson to describe a period of inner conflict and confusion during adolescence when individuals struggle to define who they are and what role they will play in society. This stage is part of Eriksonâ€™s psychosocial theory and typically occurs between ages 12â€“18.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			During this phase, adolescents explore various roles, beliefs, values, and relationships as they attempt to form a coherent sense of self. However, if they fail to resolve this conflict successfully, they may experience role confusion â€” a lack of clarity about personal values, goals, or place in society.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Causes of Identity Crisis:</strong><br>
			Several factors contribute to identity crises during adolescence:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Physical changes:</strong> Hormonal shifts and body development influence self-perception.</li>
			<li><strong>Social pressure:</strong> Peer groups, social media, and societal expectations shape self-image and aspirations.</li>
			<li><strong>Cognitive growth:</strong> Increased abstract thinking allows deeper exploration of self but also causes uncertainty.</li>
			<li><strong>Family dynamics:</strong> Shifting relationships with parents and increased autonomy lead to re-evaluation of family roles.</li>
			<li><strong>Educational transitions:</strong> Decisions about education and career paths increase stress and self-doubt.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Resolution Strategies:</strong><br>
			Resolving an identity crisis involves a process of exploration and commitment. Key strategies include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Exploration:</strong> Encouraging adolescents to try different roles, hobbies, and belief systems helps them discover what aligns with their values and interests.</li>
			<li><strong>Mentorship:</strong> Positive adult role models provide guidance and support during this transition.</li>
			<li><strong>Open communication:</strong> Parents and teachers should foster safe environments where adolescents feel comfortable discussing doubts and concerns.</li>
			<li><strong>Self-reflection:</strong> Journals, creative expression, and mindfulness practices help adolescents articulate feelings and gain clarity.</li>
			<li><strong>Psychological support:</strong> When identity confusion leads to anxiety, depression, or behavioral issues, professional counseling can facilitate resolution.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			James Marcia expanded Eriksonâ€™s concept by identifying four identity statuses:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Identity Diffusion:</strong> No exploration or commitment</li>
			<li><strong>Foreclosure:</strong> Commitment made without exploration</li>
			<li><strong>Moratorium:</strong> Active exploration with no firm commitment</li>
			<li><strong>Identity Achievement:</strong> Exploration followed by commitment</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Adolescents experiencing identity moratorium may appear indecisive or rebellious, but this is a natural part of development. With time and support, most individuals move toward identity achievement.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In conclusion, identity crisis is a normal developmental challenge during adolescence. It reflects the adolescent's quest for meaning and purpose. With supportive environments, opportunities for exploration, and emotional guidance, adolescents can emerge with a strong, integrated sense of identity that supports psychological well-being and healthy decision-making.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
