	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-red-800 text-lg">Define and describe identity and identity crisis in adolescence.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-red-100 border-red-200">
		  <p>
			<strong>Identity</strong> refers to the internalized sense of self that evolves over time through experiences, choices, and reflection. According to Erik Erikson, identity formation is a central task of adolescence, occurring during the fifth psychosocial stage: <strong>identity vs role confusion</strong>.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Identity encompasses several dimensions:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Personal identity:</strong> Awareness of one's personality traits, values, and goals.</li>
			<li><strong>Social identity:</strong> Identification with peer groups, culture, gender, and other affiliations.</li>
			<li><strong>Sexual identity:</strong> Understanding of sexual orientation and gender identity.</li>
			<li><strong>Occupational identity:</strong> Emerging awareness of future career roles and life path.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Identity Crisis:</strong><br>
			An identity crisis occurs when adolescents face significant confusion and uncertainty regarding these aspects of self. It is marked by frequent changes in appearance, beliefs, or relationships as the individual experiments with different identities.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Erikson described this as a â€œpsychosocial moratoriumâ€ â€” a time when society permits adolescents to delay permanent decisions while exploring options. Without sufficient exploration or support, adolescents may fall into <strong>role confusion</strong>, where they adopt identities imposed by others without personal reflection.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			James Marcia expanded this framework by proposing that identity develops along two dimensions: <em>exploration</em> and <em>commitment</em>. Based on these, he identified four identity statuses:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Diffusion:</strong> No exploration or commitment</li>
			<li><strong>Foreclosure:</strong> Premature commitment without exploration</li>
			<li><strong>Moratorium:</strong> Exploration without firm commitment</li>
			<li><strong>Achievement:</strong> Exploration followed by commitment</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Supporting Healthy Identity Formation:</strong><br>
			Adults can help by:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Providing safe spaces for self-expression</li>
			<li>Encouraging critical thinking and independent decision-making</li>
			<li>Modeling healthy values and coping strategies</li>
			<li>Validating struggles rather than dismissing them</li>
			<li>Offering diverse opportunities for involvement (e.g., clubs, internships, travel)</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Identity development is not a one-time event but a lifelong process. Adolescence, however, is a crucial window for laying the foundation of a coherent, stable identity that guides behavior and decision-making in adulthood.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
