	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-green-800 text-lg">Differentiate between self-concept and self-esteem. Describe signs of negative self-concept in adolescents.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-green-100 border-green-200">
		  <p>
			<strong>Self-concept</strong> and <strong>self-esteem</strong> are related yet distinct components of self-understanding that play a critical role in adolescent development.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Self-Concept:</strong><br>
			Self-concept is the cognitive component of self â€” how individuals perceive themselves across various domains such as academic ability, physical appearance, social competence, and moral values. It is multidimensional and often based on real or perceived attributes.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			For example, an adolescent might think, "I am good at math" or "Iâ€™m shy around new people." These beliefs collectively form a personâ€™s self-concept.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Self-Esteem:</strong><br>
			Self-esteem is the affective evaluation of the self â€” how much value or worth an individual places on themselves. It reflects whether a person sees themselves positively or negatively overall.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			While self-concept is descriptive ("I am smart"), self-esteem is evaluative ("I feel proud because I am smart"). Self-esteem fluctuates more than self-concept and is influenced by external validation, feedback, and success/failure experiences.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Differences:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <table class="w-full table-auto mt-4 border-collapse border border-gray-300">
			<thead>
			  <tr class="bg-green-200">
				<th class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Aspect</th>
				<th class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Self-Concept</th>
				<th class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Self-Esteem</th>
			  </tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2">Definition</td>
				<td class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2">What you believe about yourself</td>
				<td class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2">How you feel about those beliefs</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2">Nature</td>
				<td class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2">Cognitive</td>
				<td class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2">Emotional</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2">Stability</td>
				<td class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2">Relatively stable</td>
				<td class="border border-green-300 px-4 py-2">Fluctuating</td>
			  </tr>
			</tbody>
		  </table>

		  <p class="mt-4">
			<strong>Negative Self-Concept in Adolescents:</strong><br>
			A negative self-concept can manifest in multiple ways, especially during adolescence when self-awareness intensifies. Common signs include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mt-2 mb-4">
			<li>Consistently describing oneself in negative terms (â€œIâ€™m stupid,â€ â€œNo one likes meâ€)</li>
			<li>Avoiding challenges due to fear of failure or inadequacy</li>
			<li>Low motivation and disengagement from school or social activities</li>
			<li>Excessive comparison with peers, often feeling inferior</li>
			<li>Difficulty making decisions or expressing opinions</li>
			<li>Withdrawal from family or friends</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Implications:</strong><br>
			Negative self-concept can lead to low self-esteem, depression, and poor academic performance. It may also result in maladaptive behaviors like aggression, substance use, or risky sexual behavior as a way to seek validation or escape pain.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Interventions:</strong><br>
			Building a positive self-concept involves:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Promoting mastery experiences (success in academics, sports, arts)</li>
			<li>Providing constructive feedback and recognition</li>
			<li>Encouraging meaningful goal-setting</li>
			<li>Fostering secure attachment and emotional support</li>
			<li>Teaching resilience and adaptive coping skills</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			In summary, while self-concept is the mental picture one holds of oneself, self-esteem is the emotional response to that image. Supporting adolescents in developing a realistic and positive self-concept lays the groundwork for healthy self-esteem and psychological adjustment.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
