	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-indigo-800 text-lg">Explain the process of developing identity and identity crisis during adolescence.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-indigo-100 border-indigo-200">
		  <p>
			The development of identity during adolescence is a complex, dynamic process shaped by biological, cognitive, and social influences. According to Erik Erikson, adolescence is the stage of <strong>identity vs role confusion</strong>, where individuals grapple with questions like â€œWho am I?â€ and â€œWhat is my place in the world?â€
		  </p>

		  <p>
			James Marcia expanded on Eriksonâ€™s work by identifying four identity statuses based on two key dimensions: <em>exploration</em> and <em>commitment</em>.
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Identity Diffusion:</strong> No active exploration or commitment</li>
			<li><strong>Foreclosure:</strong> Commitment made without exploration (often influenced by parents or authority figures)</li>
			<li><strong>Moratorium:</strong> Active exploration with no clear commitment (common in early adolescence)</li>
			<li><strong>Identity Achievement:</strong> Exploration followed by a firm commitment</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			<strong>Key Influences on Identity Formation:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Peer Groups:</strong> Adolescents often explore identity through affiliation with subcultures, fashion, music, or ideologies.</li>
			<li><strong>Family:</strong> Family values and expectations significantly influence identity, though adolescents may reject or accept these over time.</li>
			<li><strong>Media and Technology:</strong> Exposure to diverse lifestyles and identities via digital platforms broadens self-perception but can also create confusion.</li>
			<li><strong>Education and Career Exploration:</strong> Academic performance, extracurricular participation, and vocational interest shape occupational identity.</li>
			<li><strong>Gender and Sexual Orientation:</strong> Adolescents begin to understand and express their gender identity and sexual orientation, which plays a major role in self-definition.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Identity Crisis:</strong><br>
			An identity crisis arises when adolescents struggle to reconcile conflicting messages from within and outside themselves. They may frequently change values, friendships, or beliefs as they search for coherence. If unresolved, this can lead to confusion, anxiety, and difficulty forming lasting relationships or pursuing long-term goals.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Resolving Identity Conflicts:</strong><br>
			Resolution involves:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Engaging in varied life experiences</li>
			<li>Reflecting on personal values and goals</li>
			<li>Developing a consistent narrative of self</li>
			<li>Receiving affirmation and support from trusted adults</li>
			<li>Learning to integrate contradictions and complexities of self</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Although identity formation is not fully complete by late adolescence, most individuals gradually move toward greater integration and stability. Supportive environments that encourage exploration and provide structure aid in navigating this critical developmental milestone.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>


	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-yellow-800 text-lg">Describe the process of development of identity and its crisis during adolescence.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-yellow-100 border-yellow-200">
		  <p>
			The process of identity development during adolescence is a multifaceted journey involving self-exploration, social interaction, and personal reflection. It marks a shift from childhood dependence to increasing autonomy and self-definition.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Stages of Identity Development:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Early Adolescence (12â€“14 years):</strong> Begins with emerging self-awareness and experimentation. Teens may adopt temporary identities or mimic role models.</li>
			<li><strong>Middle Adolescence (15â€“17 years):</strong> Intense exploration of values, relationships, and future roles. Identity begins to crystallize but remains fluid.</li>
			<li><strong>Late Adolescence (18+ years):</strong> Greater clarity and commitment to values, goals, and beliefs. Identity becomes more stable and integrated.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Components of Identity:</strong><br>
			Identity is composed of several interrelated elements:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Personal Identity:</strong> Unique characteristics, values, and goals</li>
			<li><strong>Social Identity:</strong> Belonging to cultural, religious, ethnic, or peer-based groups</li>
			<li><strong>Sexual Identity:</strong> Understanding of gender, sexuality, and intimacy</li>
			<li><strong>Vocational Identity:</strong> Awareness of career interests and life direction</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Identity Crisis:</strong><br>
			An identity crisis occurs when adolescents face intense internal conflict and confusion about who they are and where they fit in the world. This can manifest as:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Extreme shifts in values or lifestyle</li>
			<li>Alienation from family and peers</li>
			<li>Struggles with morality, religion, or political views</li>
			<li>Feelings of isolation or emptiness</li>
			<li>Risk-taking behavior as a means of self-expression</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Identity crises are not inherently pathological; they are a normal part of development. However, prolonged or unresolved identity confusion can lead to emotional distress and difficulties in interpersonal functioning.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Resolution and Support:</strong><br>
			Resolving identity conflicts requires:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Opportunities to explore diverse experiences and perspectives</li>
			<li>Guidance from mentors, counselors, or trusted adults</li>
			<li>Safe spaces for open dialogue about self and future</li>
			<li>Encouragement of reflective practices (journaling, art, discussions)</li>
			<li>Positive reinforcement of effort and progress, not just outcomes</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Schools, families, and communities play a vital role in providing adolescents with resources and encouragement to navigate this critical developmental stage effectively.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
