	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-blue-800 text-lg">Explain emotional development during early school years.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-blue-100 border-blue-200">
		  <p>
			Emotional development during the early school years (ages 6â€“9) involves expanding emotional awareness, improving regulation, and learning socially acceptable ways to express feelings.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Children become better at identifying and labeling emotions such as frustration, jealousy, pride, and guilt. They also learn to understand others' emotions â€” a key aspect of empathy and social competence.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			This stage sees significant growth in self-regulation. With improved attention and executive functioning, children can delay gratification, manage impulses, and respond to frustration more constructively.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Emotional development is supported by:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Social Interactions:</strong> Peer relationships teach conflict resolution and emotional expression.</li>
			<li><strong>Teacher Feedback:</strong> Constructive responses help students interpret success and failure.</li>
			<li><strong>Home Environment:</strong> Supportive parenting fosters secure emotional expression and coping skills.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Some children may struggle with emotional dysregulation due to temperament, trauma, or environmental stressors. These challenges can affect classroom behavior and peer relations if not addressed early.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Schools play a crucial role in promoting emotional literacy through programs like SEL (Social-Emotional Learning), which teaches self-awareness, self-management, responsible decision-making, and relationship skills.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
