		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>
	  
	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-purple-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-purple-800 text-lg">Causes underlying acknowledging sexuality and high risk behaviours during adolescence.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-purple-100 border-purple-200">
		  <p>
			Acknowledging sexuality and engaging in high-risk behaviors are common during adolescence due to a combination of biological, psychological, and sociocultural factors. These behaviors reflect the adolescent's search for identity, peer acceptance, and independence.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Biological Factors:</strong><br>
			Hormonal changes during puberty trigger sexual maturation and heightened sensitivity to pleasure. The brain's reward system becomes more responsive to dopamine, increasing susceptibility to thrill-seeking and impulsive behavior.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			At the same time, the prefrontal cortex â€” responsible for impulse control and decision-making â€” is still developing. This imbalance makes adolescents more prone to risks such as unprotected sex, substance use, reckless driving, and delinquency.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Psychological Factors:</strong><br>
			Adolescence is a time of identity exploration and emotional volatility. Many teens experiment with different roles and behaviors as they seek to establish a coherent self-concept. Acknowledging and expressing sexuality is a core part of this process.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Emotional regulation is still immature, so some adolescents turn to risky behaviors as a form of emotional release or coping mechanism for stress, loneliness, or trauma.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Sociocultural Influences:</strong><br>
			Peer pressure plays a powerful role. Adolescents often conform to group norms to gain approval and avoid rejection. In many cultures, sexual experimentation and sensation-seeking behavior are seen as rites of passage or symbols of maturity.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Media and digital platforms further normalize certain types of sexual behavior and risk-taking through exposure to movies, music, social media, and pornography.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Developmental Vulnerabilities:</strong><br>
			Adolescents may lack the judgment to foresee consequences or resist peer influence. Some may engage in risky behavior to assert autonomy, test boundaries, or rebel against parental or societal expectations.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Those with unstable home environments, low self-esteem, or histories of abuse may be especially vulnerable to early sexual activity and substance use as coping mechanisms.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Prevention and Intervention:</strong><br>
			Addressing these behaviors requires:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Comprehensive sex education that includes emotional intelligence and consent</li>
			<li>Parental communication about sexuality and risk</li>
			<li>Access to health services and counseling</li>
			<li>Positive peer modeling and engagement in prosocial activities</li>
			<li>Building resilience and coping skills through school programs or therapy</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Expression of Sexuality:</strong><br>
			Adolescents may express sexuality in various ways:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Curiosity about sexual anatomy and functions</li>
			<li>Attraction to peers and initial romantic experiences</li>
			<li>Questioning sexual orientation (e.g., identifying as gay, lesbian, bisexual, questioning)</li>
			<li>Exploring gender identity (e.g., identifying as transgender, non-binary)</li>
			<li>Experimentation with kissing, dating, or sexual behavior</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Healthy Acknowledgment:</strong><br>
			Healthy sexual development includes:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Accurate knowledge about sex and relationships</li>
			<li>Ability to set boundaries and practice consent</li>
			<li>Resilience against peer pressure and unhealthy influences</li>
			<li>Open communication with trusted adults or professionals</li>
			<li>Acceptance of diversity in sexual and gender identities</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Educational programs that include comprehensive sexuality education, emotional literacy, and inclusivity help adolescents navigate this aspect of development in a safe and affirming manner.
		  </p>
		  
		  <p>
			By understanding the root causes behind these behaviors, educators and caregivers can offer informed support that promotes healthy development and reduces harm.
		  </p>

