	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-teal-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-teal-800 text-lg">High risk behaviour and coping with loss of normalcy during adolescence.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-teal-100 border-teal-200">
		  <p>
			Adolescence is a transitional period marked by exploration, identity formation, and adaptation to changing circumstances. It is also a time when teens may engage in high-risk behaviors and face disruptions in daily routines or expectations â€” what is often referred to as â€œloss of normalcy.â€
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>High-Risk Behaviors:</strong><br>
			High-risk behaviors include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Substance use (alcohol, drugs)</li>
			<li>Unprotected sexual activity</li>
			<li>Delinquent behavior (vandalism, theft)</li>
			<li>Reckless driving or dangerous stunts</li>
			<li>Self-harm or suicidal ideation</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			These behaviors often serve as mechanisms for dealing with stress, seeking peer approval, or asserting independence. However, they pose serious threats to physical and psychological well-being.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Loss of Normalcy:</strong><br>
			Adolescents may experience a sense of disrupted routine due to:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Family instability (divorce, relocation, economic hardship)</li>
			<li>Academic pressures or failures</li>
			<li>Health issues or chronic illness</li>
			<li>Social exclusion or bullying</li>
			<li>Major life events (death, disaster, global crises)</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			During such times, teens may feel confused, isolated, or anxious. Their usual sources of comfort or structure may become unavailable, increasing vulnerability to emotional distress and behavioral problems.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Coping Mechanisms:</strong><br>
			Adolescents cope with these challenges in diverse ways:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Adaptive Coping:</strong> Talking to trusted adults, journaling, engaging in sports, volunteering, or creative pursuits</li>
			<li><strong>Maladaptive Coping:</strong> Substance use, withdrawal, aggression, or risky sexual behavior</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Role of Support Systems:</strong><br>
			Supportive environments are essential for helping adolescents manage high-risk behaviors and adapt to disruptions:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Family:</strong> Open communication, emotional availability, and consistency reduce confusion and distress.</li>
			<li><strong>School:</strong> Counseling services, peer support groups, and inclusive curricula promote resilience.</li>
			<li><strong>Community:</strong> Access to youth centers, mentorship programs, and recreational activities offers safe outlets for expression and belonging.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Conclusion:</strong><br>
			Adolescence is a time of transformation, and occasional risk-taking is a natural part of development. However, when high-risk behaviors persist or occur alongside a sense of lost normalcy, timely intervention is necessary to prevent long-term consequences and support healthy adjustment.
		  </p>

