	  </details>


	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-blue-800 text-lg">Explain development during adult years. Compare stage theories and contextual approach.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-blue-100 border-blue-200">
		  <p>
			Adult development refers to the psychological, social, and emotional changes that occur from early adulthood through old age. Unlike childhood and adolescence, which are marked by visible physical changes, adult development focuses on internal transformations â€” identity, relationships, career, and meaning-making.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Two major approaches explain adult development: <strong>stage theories</strong> and <strong>contextual theories</strong>.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Stage Theories:</strong><br>
			These propose that development occurs in fixed sequences or stages. Notable examples include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Erik Erikson:</strong> Identity vs Role Confusion â†’ Intimacy vs Isolation â†’ Generativity vs Stagnation â†’ Integrity vs Despair</li>
			<li><strong>Daniel Levinson:</strong> Life structure model involving transitions like entering adulthood, midlife crisis, and late adulthood</li>
			<li><strong>Kohlbergâ€™s Moral Development:</strong> Expands into adulthood with postconventional morality</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Stage theories emphasize universal patterns and assume all individuals progress through similar phases. They provide a structured framework for understanding life transitions but may oversimplify individual differences.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Contextual Approach:</strong><br>
			This perspective argues that adult development is shaped by personal experiences, culture, history, and environment. It emphasizes variability, flexibility, and lifelong learning. Key ideas include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Development is not linear but dynamic and influenced by life events</li>
			<li>People construct meaning based on their unique contexts (family, work, health)</li>
			<li>There is no single "correct" path through adulthood</li>
			<li>Change can occur at any point due to external or internal factors</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			The contextual approach allows for greater individual variation and recognizes how gender, race, socioeconomic status, and cultural background influence developmental trajectories.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Comparison:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <table class="w-full table-auto mt-4 border-collapse border border-gray-300">
			<thead>
			  <tr class="bg-blue-200">
				<th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Aspect</th>
				<th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Stage Theories</th>
				<th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Contextual Approach</th>
			  </tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Structure</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Predictable sequence of stages</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Non-linear, flexible progression</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Universality</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Assumes common developmental path</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Highlights diversity and individual differences</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Influence</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Internal, biological, and cognitive maturation</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Social, historical, and environmental influences</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Flexibility</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Fixed order and timing</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Adaptive and variable across lifetimes</td>
			  </tr>
			</tbody>
		  </table>

		  <p class="mt-4">
			While stage theories offer clarity and predictability, they often fail to capture the complexity of real-life experiences. Contextual theories, though less rigid, provide a more holistic view of development by integrating personal narratives and sociocultural factors.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In practice, a combination of both perspectives offers the most comprehensive understanding. Stage models help identify broad developmental themes, while contextual models allow for personalized interpretations and interventions.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>
	  
	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-orange-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-orange-800 text-lg">Write a note on coping with loss of normalcy during adolescence.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-orange-100 border-orange-200">
		  <p>
			Adolescence is a time of profound change, and any disruption to expected patterns of life can cause a sense of <strong>loss of normalcy</strong>. Whether due to personal, familial, or societal upheaval, teens may struggle to adjust, leading to emotional distress, disorientation, and behavioral issues.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Common Causes of Loss of Normalcy:</strong><br>
			- Parental divorce or separation<br>
			- Death of a loved one<br>
			- Relocation or school change<br>
			- Chronic illness or disability<br>
			- Natural disasters or pandemics<br>
			- Bullying or discrimination
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Impact on Adolescents:</strong><br>
			Due to their developmental stage, adolescents are particularly sensitive to disruptions in routine and relationships. The effects may include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Increased anxiety and mood swings</li>
			<li>Decline in academic performance</li>
			<li>Withdrawal from family and friends</li>
			<li>Anger outbursts or irritability</li>
			<li>Engagement in risky behaviors as a form of escapism</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Healthy Coping Strategies:</strong><br>
			Adolescents can be supported through:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Emotional Expression:</strong> Encourage journaling, talking, or creative outlets like art or music.</li>
			<li><strong>Structure:</strong> Re-establish predictable routines to restore a sense of control.</li>
			<li><strong>Connection:</strong> Promote peer and family bonding through shared activities and open conversations.</li>
			<li><strong>Professional Help:</strong> Counselors or therapists can guide teens through emotional processing and coping techniques.</li>
			<li><strong>Goal Setting:</strong> Help teens identify short-term, achievable goals to regain a sense of agency.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Role of Adults:</strong><br>
			Parents and educators should:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Validate the teenâ€™s emotions rather than minimizing them</li>
			<li>Provide age-appropriate information about the situation</li>
			<li>Maintain consistent emotional support and presence</li>
			<li>Encourage participation in decision-making and problem-solving</li>
			<li>Monitor for warning signs of depression or trauma</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Conclusion:</strong><br>
			Coping with loss of normalcy is a challenging but manageable process. With appropriate support, adolescents can adapt to new realities and even grow from adversity, building resilience and emotional strength for future life challenges.
		  </p>

