	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-yellow-800 text-lg">Elucidate the cognitive changes during middle adulthood period.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-yellow-100 border-yellow-200">
		  <p>
			Middle adulthood (ages 40â€“65) is a transitional phase where cognitive development begins to shift. Though most individuals remain cognitively capable, subtle changes occur across various domains.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Information Processing Speed:</strong><br>
			Cognitive processing slows down slightly. Tasks that once felt effortless â€” like quickly solving problems or switching between tasks â€” may take longer.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Memory Function:</strong><br>
			Short-term memory capacity remains largely unchanged, but retrieval becomes slower. For example, recalling names or dates may take more effort.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Prospective memory â€” remembering to do things in the future â€” may decline, increasing forgetfulness of appointments or routines.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Executive Functioning:</strong><br>
			Executive functions such as planning, organization, and multitasking begin to show signs of slowing. Decision-making may take longer, especially under pressure.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			However, emotional regulation and strategic thinking often improve due to life experience and increased metacognition.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Knowledge and Wisdom:</strong><br>
			Crystallized intelligence â€” knowledge, vocabulary, and world understanding â€” continues to grow. Middle-aged adults excel at contextual reasoning, drawing conclusions, and applying life lessons.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			This makes them valuable mentors and leaders, even if they may not perform as well on standardized tests requiring speed or novelty.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Problem Solving and Creativity:</strong><br>
			Creative thinking and practical problem-solving remain strong. Adults in this stage often refine their expertise and apply creativity within their profession or personal life.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>6. Learning New Skills:</strong><br>
			Learning new technologies or languages may take more time and effort compared to younger adults. However, with practice and motivation, middle-aged adults can still acquire new skills effectively.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>7. Emotional Intelligence:</strong><br>
			Emotional intelligence peaks during middle adulthood. Adults become better at managing interpersonal conflicts, reading emotions, and regulating their own responses.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Supporting Cognitive Health:</strong><br>
			To promote cognitive vitality:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Stay physically active</li>
			<li>Engage in mentally stimulating activities</li>
			<li>Maintain social networks</li>
			<li>Manage stress and ensure adequate rest</li>
			<li>Eat a brain-healthy diet (rich in antioxidants, omega-3s)</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Overall, middle adulthood is characterized by cognitive refinement rather than decline. With proper lifestyle habits, adults can sustain high-level functioning well into later life.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
