	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-red-800 text-lg">Compare stage theories and contextual approach to development during this period.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-red-100 border-red-200">
		  <p>
			The developmental period under discussion (often early to middle adulthood) can be interpreted through two contrasting lenses: <strong>stage theories</strong> and <strong>contextual approaches</strong>.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Stage Theories:</strong><br>
			Stage-based models like those of Erikson and Levinson propose that adult development follows a predictable pattern:
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Early Adulthood:</strong> Identity formation, intimacy building</li>
			<li><strong>Middle Adulthood:</strong> Generativity vs stagnation, midlife transitions</li>
			<li><strong>Late Adulthood:</strong> Ego integrity vs despair</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			These theories emphasize internal psychological conflicts and assume that everyone moves through similar life phases at comparable ages.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			For example, Eriksonâ€™s <strong>generativity vs stagnation</strong> stage assumes that most adults between 40â€“65 years grapple with contributing to future generations.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Contextual Approach:</strong><br>
			The contextual model argues that development is shaped by:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Sociocultural background</li>
			<li>Economic and political environment</li>
			<li>Life events and personal choices</li>
			<li>Gender, ethnicity, and socioeconomic status</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Unlike stage theories, it does not assume a uniform progression. Instead, it recognizes that people may experience life transitions differently based on their unique circumstances.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			For instance, a woman who delays career for parenting may enter generativity later than someone who builds a professional identity earlier. Similarly, global crises, migration, or trauma can alter traditional pathways.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Key Differences:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <table class="w-full table-auto mt-4 border-collapse border border-gray-300">
			<thead>
			  <tr class="bg-red-200">
				<th class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Aspect</th>
				<th class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Stage Theories</th>
				<th class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Contextual Approach</th>
			  </tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Structure</td>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Predictable sequence of stages</td>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Non-linear, flexible progression</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Universality</td>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Assumes common developmental path</td>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Highlights diversity and individual differences</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Influence</td>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Internal, biological, and cognitive maturation</td>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Social, historical, and environmental influences</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Change Mechanism</td>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Driven by internal psychological conflict</td>
				<td class="border border-red-300 px-4 py-2">Shaped by life events, relationships, and context</td>
			  </tr>
			</tbody>
		  </table>

		  <p class="mt-4">
			<strong>Application in Real Life:</strong><br>
			- Stage theories help educators and therapists anticipate typical challenges<br>
			- Contextual theories aid in designing personalized interventions based on life experiences
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In conclusion, while stage theories offer a structured framework for interpreting adult development, contextual theories provide a broader, more inclusive lens that accounts for variability and complexity.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-yellow-800 text-lg">Explain the concept of ageing. Discuss ageing issues during early/middle adulthood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-yellow-100 border-yellow-200">
		  <p>
			Ageing is a natural, progressive process that affects every aspect of human functioning â€” physical, cognitive, emotional, and social. Though commonly associated with late adulthood, signs of ageing begin much earlier and evolve gradually throughout life.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Ageing in Early Adulthood (25â€“40 years):</strong><br>
			Although early adulthood is generally a time of peak performance, subtle signs of ageing appear:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Physical:</strong> Metabolism begins to slow; muscle mass starts to decrease slightly; skin elasticity decreases</li>
			<li><strong>Cognitive:</strong> Peak intellectual performance is maintained, but some studies show slight declines in processing speed</li>
			<li><strong>Emotional:</strong> Increased awareness of time and mortality; pressure to establish life goals</li>
			<li><strong>Social:</strong> Shift from peer-oriented to family and career-focused life</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Ageing in Middle Adulthood (40â€“65 years):</strong><br>
			Biological changes become more pronounced:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Physical:</strong> Menopause in women, andropause in men, decreased bone density, increased risk of cardiovascular diseases</li>
			<li><strong>Cognitive:</strong> Crystallized intelligence remains strong, but fluid intelligence may decline slightly</li>
			<li><strong>Psychosocial:</strong> Concerns about life review, legacy, and future plans intensify</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Key Ageing Issues:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Body Image and Self-perception:</strong> Appearance changes (gray hair, wrinkles) affect self-esteem and confidence</li>
			<li><strong>Workplace Challenges:</strong> Age discrimination, reduced mobility, or difficulty keeping up with technological changes</li>
			<li><strong>Health Awareness:</strong> Greater attention to diet, exercise, and preventive healthcare</li>
			<li><strong>Family Dynamics:</strong> Children leaving home, caring for elderly parents, and marital renegotiation</li>
			<li><strong>Existential Reflection:</strong> Reassessing life goals, values, and accomplishments</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Impact of Sociocultural Factors:</strong><br>
			Cultural attitudes toward ageing vary widely. In youth-centered societies, early signs of ageing may provoke anxiety or depression. In cultures that value wisdom and experience, these changes are embraced as markers of maturity.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Strategies for Healthy Ageing:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Regular health check-ups and preventive care</li>
			<li>Engaging in lifelong learning and mental stimulation</li>
			<li>Maintaining active social and familial relationships</li>
			<li>Practicing mindfulness, gratitude, and emotional regulation</li>
			<li>Remaining physically active and nutritionally balanced</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Understanding and embracing the concept of ageing as a continuous process helps individuals make proactive choices that enhance quality of life and promote resilience in later years.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
