	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-indigo-800 text-lg">Discuss psychosocial changes during middle adulthood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-indigo-100 border-indigo-200">
		  <p>
			Middle adulthood (approximately 40â€“65 years) is a period of significant psychosocial transformation. It involves shifts in identity, relationships, and life purpose, often accompanied by internal reflection and external pressures.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Identity Reassessment:</strong><br>
			Eriksonâ€™s <strong>generativity vs stagnation</strong> stage highlights the tension between contributing to future generations and feeling unproductive. Those who engage in meaningful roles â€” such as parenting, mentoring, or community involvement â€” tend to feel fulfilled. Others may feel stuck or unaccomplished, leading to dissatisfaction.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Family Transitions:</strong><br>
			This stage often includes:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Empty nest syndrome</li>
			<li>Caring for aging parents</li>
			<li>Changes in spousal dynamics</li>
			<li>Supporting adult children</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			These transitions challenge traditional family roles and require emotional flexibility and resilience.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Career and Work Life:</strong><br>
			Middle adulthood often brings career advancement, plateauing, or even change. Some individuals pursue second careers or retire early, while others continue working full-time. Job satisfaction and work-life balance become critical concerns.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Health and Aging:</strong><br>
			Physical decline becomes more noticeable. Energy levels drop, metabolism slows, and chronic conditions may appear. Emotional awareness of aging increases, prompting lifestyle changes or existential reflection.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Social Roles and Responsibilities:</strong><br>
			Many middle-aged adults hold leadership roles in communities, organizations, and families. They serve as mentors, advisors, and role models, often experiencing a shift from doing to guiding.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>6. Cognitive and Emotional Maturation:</strong><br>
			Emotional intelligence improves significantly during this stage. People become better at managing stress, regulating emotions, and understanding complex interpersonal dynamics.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>7. Existential Reflection:</strong><br>
			Questions about lifeâ€™s meaning, legacy, and mortality arise. This can lead to spiritual exploration, creative expression, or philosophical inquiry.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Common Psychological Responses:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Increased concern about time and mortality</li>
			<li>Midlife crisis or renewal</li>
			<li>Desire to leave a legacy</li>
			<li>Growing acceptance of limitations</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			In summary, middle adulthood is a rich and complex phase characterized by increased self-awareness, shifting social roles, and deeper emotional insight. These psychosocial changes reflect an ongoing effort to find balance between giving and receiving, doing and reflecting, and being and becoming.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>






	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-green-800 text-lg">Discuss the developmental tasks of middle adulthood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-green-100 border-green-200">
		  <p>
			Middle adulthood, typically spanning ages 40 to 65, is marked by significant psychological, social, and physical transitions. Robert Havighurst identified several developmental tasks during this period, emphasizing the need to adapt to changing life circumstances and responsibilities.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Havighurstâ€™s Developmental Tasks:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Achieving adult civic and social responsibility</strong>: Contributing to community and society becomes increasingly important during this phase.</li>
			<li><strong>Establishing and maintaining a satisfactory occupation</strong>: Many adults seek job satisfaction, stability, and possibly mentorship roles.</li>
			<li><strong>Taking care of aging parents</strong>: As parents grow older, adult children often take on caregiving roles.</li>
			<li><strong>Adjusting to physiological changes</strong>: Physical changes such as menopause, declining energy levels, and reduced sensory abilities become more apparent.</li>
			<li><strong>Maintaining a satisfying marital relationship</strong>: Couples navigate new challenges like empty nest syndrome, retirement planning, and evolving intimacy.</li>
			<li><strong>Rearing children until independence</strong>: Supporting adolescents and helping them transition into adulthood remains a key task.</li>
			<li><strong>Developing leisure-time activities</strong>: With professional and parenting roles shifting, finding fulfilling hobbies and recreation becomes essential.</li>
			<li><strong>Accepting and adjusting to middle age</strong>: Reflecting on accomplishments, re-evaluating goals, and accepting mortality are central themes.</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			<strong>Eriksonâ€™s View â€“ Generativity vs Stagnation:</strong><br>
			Erikson described middle adulthood as a time when people either feel generative â€” contributing to future generations through parenting, mentoring, or creative work â€” or experience stagnation, feeling unproductive and disconnected.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Generativity involves nurturing, guiding, and creating, while stagnation reflects self-absorption and lack of contribution. Midlife crises often emerge when individuals perceive a mismatch between current achievements and personal ideals.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Psychological Adjustments:</strong><br>
			Adults in this stage face complex emotional adjustments:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Coming to terms with aging and mortality</li>
			<li>Reassessing career goals and life direction</li>
			<li>Navigating changes in family roles</li>
			<li>Managing financial and health-related concerns</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Societal Expectations:</strong><br>
			Society often places high demands on middle-aged adults â€” being providers, caregivers, mentors, and decision-makers. Meeting these expectations can bring fulfillment, but failing to do so may trigger feelings of inadequacy or regret.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In conclusion, middle adulthood is a time of reflection, reassessment, and redirection. Successfully navigating its developmental tasks contributes to a sense of purpose, well-being, and legacy.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
