	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-yellow-800 text-lg">Differentiate between generativity and stagnation. Discuss for developmental tasks of middle adulthood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-yellow-100 border-yellow-200">
		  <p>
			Erik Eriksonâ€™s psychosocial theory identifies eight stages of development throughout the lifespan, with the seventh stage â€” <strong>generativity vs stagnation</strong> â€” occurring during middle adulthood (approximately ages 40â€“65). This stage centers on the individualâ€™s concern with contributing to future generations and society at large.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Generativity:</strong><br>
			Generativity refers to the desire to nurture and guide younger generations, contribute to society, and leave behind a meaningful legacy. It can manifest in various ways, such as raising children, mentoring young professionals, engaging in community service, creating art or knowledge, or contributing to workplace innovation. Individuals who achieve generativity feel productive, fulfilled, and connected to a broader purpose beyond themselves.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Stagnation:</strong><br>
			In contrast, stagnation represents a lack of investment in future generations or a sense of personal emptiness and disconnection. People experiencing stagnation may feel unproductive, self-absorbed, or disconnected from their communities. They may struggle with feelings of irrelevance or regret, particularly regarding missed opportunities for contribution or influence.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Developmental Tasks of Middle Adulthood:</strong><br>
			Middle adulthood is marked by several key developmental tasks, including:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Establishing generative roles</strong> in family, work, and community.</li>
			<li><strong>Maintaining health and vitality</strong> through lifestyle choices and preventive care.</li>
			<li><strong>Re-evaluating life goals</strong> and adjusting expectations based on changing circumstances.</li>
			<li><strong>Supporting aging parents</strong> while managing responsibilities to children and spouse.</li>
			<li><strong>Navigating career transitions</strong> such as promotions, job changes, or retirement planning.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Successfully navigating these tasks contributes to a sense of integrity and fulfillment, whereas failure may lead to dissatisfaction, depression, or identity confusion. Erikson emphasized that generativity is not limited to biological parenthood but encompasses any act of giving back and fostering the well-being of others.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
