	<!-- Question Card: Late Adulthood / Old Age -->
	<div class="question-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-xl border border-indigo-200">
	  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-indigo-700 mb-5 flex items-center">
		<span class="mr-2">ðŸ”¹</span> Late Adulthood / Old Age
	  </h3>

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-red-800 text-lg">How does Erikson's and Levinson's theory highlight the psychosocial changes during early adulthood?</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-red-100 border-red-200">
		  <p>
			Erik Erikson and Daniel Levinson both proposed influential theories that illuminate psychosocial development during early adulthood, though they differ in focus and methodology.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Eriksonâ€™s Psychosocial Theory:</strong><br>
			Erikson described early adulthood as the stage of <strong>intimacy vs isolation</strong>. This period involves forming deep, meaningful connections with others while maintaining a sense of self. Failure to form such bonds may lead to loneliness, withdrawal, or fear of commitment.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Erikson emphasized that successful navigation of this stage requires resolving earlier conflicts â€” particularly those around identity formation. Individuals must be clear about who they are before they can fully commit to another person or cause.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			He also viewed early adulthood as a time of exploration and experimentation â€” choosing partners, careers, and lifestyles. This aligns with the broader theme of psychosocial moratorium, where young adults explore roles without permanent commitments.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Levinsonâ€™s Life Structure Model:</strong><br>
			Levinson saw early adulthood as part of a larger life cycle, beginning with the transition to adulthood (ages 17â€“22) and continuing through early adulthood (22â€“28). He introduced the idea of a â€œdreamâ€ â€” a vision of future life built on values, goals, and aspirations.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			During early adulthood (22â€“28), individuals begin building a stable life structure by making key choices in areas such as:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Occupational identity</li>
			<li>Relationships and family planning</li>
			<li>Social and political views</li>
			<li>Self-concept and life purpose</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Levinson stressed that these decisions shape the foundation of adult life and often involve balancing idealism with reality. He believed that early adulthood is a time of building and stabilizing oneâ€™s place in society.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Comparative Insights:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Erikson</strong> focuses on inner psychological conflict and interpersonal growth</li>
			<li><strong>Levinson</strong> emphasizes structural life transitions and role-building</li>
			<li>Both acknowledge early adulthood as a period of choice, change, and self-definition</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Together, these theories illustrate how early adulthood is not only a time of personal identity consolidation but also of adapting to societal expectations, forming lasting relationships, and setting life goals.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
