	  </details>
	  
	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-blue-800 text-lg">Discuss psychosocial changes during old age.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-blue-100 border-blue-200">
		  <p>
			Late adulthood, typically beginning around age 65, is marked by significant psychosocial changes. These include shifts in identity, relationships, self-perception, and life meaning as individuals adjust to physical decline, retirement, and changing roles.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Identity and Self-Perception:</strong><br>
			Older adults often experience a redefinition of self. Retirement, health changes, and loss of loved ones can challenge previous identities. Some may feel a sense of purpose through legacy-building, while others struggle with feelings of uselessness or invisibility.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Eriksonâ€™s final stage â€” <strong>ego integrity vs despair</strong> â€” captures this tension. Those who view their lives with satisfaction achieve ego integrity and face death with peace. Those with regret may experience despair, feeling that life was wasted or unfulfilled.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Social Relationships:</strong><br>
			Social circles often shrink due to deaths of peers, reduced mobility, or relocation. Loneliness and isolation are common concerns. However, many older adults maintain strong family ties and deepen bonds with grandchildren, siblings, and lifelong friends.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			The concept of â€œ<strong>social convoy</strong>â€ suggests that people move through life surrounded by a network of relationships that provide emotional support and companionship, even if it becomes smaller.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Role Transitions:</strong><br>
			Retirement, caregiving reversals, and becoming a grandparent are major role transitions in late adulthood. Some retirees find new hobbies, volunteer opportunities, or part-time work, maintaining a sense of usefulness and engagement.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Others struggle with the loss of structure, social interaction, and professional identity. Caregiving for a spouse or peer group also brings emotional strain but can enhance feelings of purpose.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Coping with Loss and Mortality:</strong><br>
			Late adulthood involves repeated exposure to loss â€” of friends, partners, independence, and eventually one's own mortality. This leads to existential reflection and spiritual inquiry for many.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Grief responses vary widely, influenced by personality, cultural context, and available support systems. Bereavement can trigger depression or anxiety if not adequately addressed.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Emotional Regulation:</strong><br>
			Research indicates that many older adults develop improved emotional regulation skills over time. They tend to focus more on positive experiences and avoid conflict, a phenomenon known as the "<strong>positivity effect</strong>."
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Despite cognitive decline in some areas, emotional wisdom and resilience often increase, contributing to greater psychological well-being.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>6. Generativity and Legacy:</strong><br>
			Even in old age, many individuals continue to contribute to future generations through storytelling, mentoring, volunteering, or creative pursuits. This reflects ongoing generativity and desire to leave a lasting impact.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In conclusion, psychosocial changes in late adulthood involve complex adaptations to physical limitations, shifting identities, and evolving relationships. With appropriate support, older adults can navigate these transitions gracefully and continue to lead fulfilling lives.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>
	  

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-red-800 text-lg">Elucidate the ageing issues and challenges in late adulthood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-red-100 border-red-200">
		  <p>
			Late adulthood brings a unique set of challenges that affect physical, psychological, and social well-being. These issues arise from biological changes, societal attitudes, and personal circumstances.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>1. Physical Decline:</strong><br>
			Age-related physiological changes such as decreased sensory acuity, slower reaction times, and chronic conditions (e.g., arthritis, hypertension) become more pronounced. Mobility decreases, making daily tasks more difficult.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Health problems like osteoporosis, heart disease, and neurodegenerative disorders (e.g., Alzheimerâ€™s, Parkinsonâ€™s) are increasingly prevalent.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>2. Cognitive Changes:</strong><br>
			While crystallized intelligence (knowledge, vocabulary) remains stable, fluid intelligence (problem-solving, memory speed) tends to decline. Working memory and attention span decrease, impacting decision-making and learning.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Although mild forgetfulness is normal, severe cognitive impairments like dementia significantly disrupt functioning and require external support.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>3. Retirement and Financial Concerns:</strong><br>
			Retirement marks a shift in lifestyle and identity. Many struggle with reduced income, uncertainty about financial security, and loss of routine.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Poor financial planning or unexpected medical expenses can lead to stress, especially when coupled with rising healthcare costs.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>4. Loss and Bereavement:</strong><br>
			Older adults often experience multiple losses â€” of friends, spouses, and even children â€” which can result in prolonged grief or depression.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			The cumulative nature of these losses may also lead to social withdrawal and disconnection from community.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>5. Changing Family Dynamics:</strong><br>
			Family roles reverse as adult children take on caregiving responsibilities. This can create dependency and emotional strain for both parties.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Intergenerational tensions may emerge regarding autonomy, living arrangements, and care decisions.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>6. Ageism and Societal Attitudes:</strong><br>
			Discrimination based on age â€” ageism â€” affects employment opportunities, access to services, and self-esteem. Society often views older adults as frail or burdensome, leading to marginalization.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>7. Mental Health Challenges:</strong><br>
			Depression, anxiety, and loneliness are more common in late adulthood. Contributing factors include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Social isolation</li>
			<li>Chronic illness</li>
			<li>Lack of meaningful activity</li>
			<li>Past unresolved trauma resurfacing</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Strategies for Coping:</strong><br>
			To manage these challenges:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Encourage social participation and intergenerational activities</li>
			<li>Provide access to mental health resources and support groups</li>
			<li>Promote physical activity and healthy lifestyle choices</li>
			<li>Support autonomy and dignity in care settings</li>
			<li>Facilitate meaningful engagement through volunteering or mentorship</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Addressing these issues holistically helps older adults age with grace, dignity, and continued contribution to society.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
