	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-green-800 text-lg">Explain the ageing process in late adulthood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-green-100 border-green-200">
		  <p>
			Ageing in late adulthood (65+ years) is a natural biological and psychological process involving gradual decline in physical functions, cognitive abilities, and adaptive capacities. It is influenced by genetics, lifestyle, and environmental factors.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Biological Changes:</strong><br>
			- Skin loses elasticity and becomes thinner<br>
			- Muscle mass declines, increasing frailty and fall risk<br>
			- Bone density reduces, raising osteoporosis likelihood<br>
			- Sensory functions like vision and hearing diminish<br>
			- Cardiovascular efficiency declines, increasing heart disease risk<br>
			- Immune system weakens, making infections more frequent
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Cognitive Changes:</strong><br>
			Cognitive decline varies among individuals. Fluid intelligence â€” involving reasoning, processing speed, and problem-solving â€” tends to decline. Crystallized intelligence â€” knowledge, vocabulary, and experience-based understanding â€” often remains stable or even improves.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Memory, particularly short-term and working memory, may show noticeable impairment. However, semantic memory and emotional intelligence often remain strong.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Psychosocial Adjustments:</strong><br>
			Late adulthood is a time of reflection and re-evaluation. Erik Erikson described this as the stage of <strong>ego integrity vs despair</strong>. Individuals either accept their life as meaningful or struggle with regrets and dissatisfaction.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Many engage in life review, revisiting past experiences and finding closure. This can be therapeutic if done constructively, though it may also trigger sadness or guilt.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Social and Environmental Influences:</strong><br>
			Retirement, widowhood, and moving to assisted living facilities are major life events that influence psychosocial adjustment. Social support plays a critical role in buffering against loneliness and depression.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Health and Lifestyle:</strong><br>
			Nutrition, physical activity, sleep quality, and mental stimulation all influence how gracefully an individual ages. Regular exercise has been shown to delay cognitive decline and improve mood and physical strength.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Positive Ageing:</strong><br>
			Successful ageing involves:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Maintaining physical and cognitive function</li>
			<li>Remaining socially engaged</li>
			<li>Continuing to pursue meaningful goals</li>
			<li>Fostering a sense of purpose and belonging</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Understanding the multifac="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>


	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-indigo-800 text-lg">Describe cognitive changes during old age.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-indigo-100 border-indigo-200">
		  <p>
			Cognitive changes during old age reflect both decline and adaptation. While certain functions deteriorate, others remain stable or even improve with experience.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Fluid Intelligence:</strong><br>
			Fluid intelligence refers to the ability to solve novel problems, reason abstractly, and think logically. This type of intelligence shows a steady decline with age. Older adults may find it harder to learn new technologies, adapt to change, or multitask efficiently.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Crystallized Intelligence:</strong><br>
			Crystallized intelligence â€” accumulated knowledge, vocabulary, and verbal reasoning â€” generally remains stable or increases into late adulthood. Older adults often have superior wisdom, judgment, and life perspective.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Memory Function:</strong><br>
			Short-term and working memory decline, affecting the ability to retain information temporarily. Long-term memory remains relatively intact, although retrieval becomes slower.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Episodic memory â€” remembering specific events â€” is more vulnerable than semantic memory â€” general knowledge and facts.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Attention and Processing Speed:</strong><br>
			Selective and divided attention may weaken, making it harder to focus amid distractions. Reaction time slows down, affecting driving and other timed activities.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Executive Functions:</strong><br>
			Executive functions like planning, organizing, and inhibitory control decline in many older adults. This affects decision-making and problem-solving abilities.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Language and Communication:</strong><br>
			Vocabulary and comprehension stay strong, but word-finding difficulties (tip-of-the-tongue moments) increase. Speech may slow, and language production may become less fluent.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Emotional Intelligence:</strong><br>
			Interestingly, emotional regulation often improves. Older adults tend to focus on positive experiences, remember them more vividly, and react less negatively to stressors â€” a phenomenon called the "positivity bias."
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Neurological Factors:</strong><br>
			Brain volume decreases, especially in prefronts and hippocampus. Synaptic connections reduce, and neurotransmitter levels fluctuate, affecting mood and cognition.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Individual Differences:</strong><br>
			Not all older adults experience cognitive decline equally. Genetics, education, mental engagement, and physical health play crucial roles in determining cognitive trajectories.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Interventions:</strong><br>
			Engaging in mentally stimulating activities (reading, puzzles), physical exercise, and social interaction can delay or mitigate cognitive decline. Lifelong learning and brain-training programs offer protective benefits.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In summary, while some cognitive abilities decline with age, others remain robust or even strengthen. Emphasizing compensatory strategies and maintaining an active lifestyle supports cognitive health in late adulthood.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>

	  

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-purple-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-purple-800 text-lg">Delineate the cognitive changes during adulthood stage.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-purple-100 border-purple-200">
		  <p>
			Adulthood spans early, middle, and late stages, each bringing distinct cognitive developments and transformations.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Early Adulthood (20â€“40 years):</strong><br>
			This is a peak period for cognitive performance. Fluid intelligence â€” including reasoning, problem-solving, and information processing â€” is at its highest.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Metacognitive skills â€” thinking about oneâ€™s own thinking â€” improve, allowing for better learning strategies, goal-setting, and self-monitoring.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Middle Adulthood (40â€“65 years):</strong><br>
			Cognitive processing speed starts to decline slightly. Multitasking and learning new skills may take more effort.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			However, crystallized intelligence â€” accumulated knowledge and expertise â€” continues to grow. Emotional intelligence and decision-making maturity also reach their peak.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Late Adulthood (65+ years):</strong><br>
			Cognitive changes become more noticeable. Short-term memory, attention span, and executive functioning decline in many individuals.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Long-term memory, vocabulary, and wisdom remain stable. Older adults may need more time to retrieve information, but accuracy remains high.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Key Cognitive Domains Affected:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <table class="w-full table-auto mt-4 border-collapse border border-gray-300">
			<thead>
			  <tr class="bg-purple-200">
				<th class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Cognitive Domain</th>
				<th class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Change During Adulthood</th>
			  </tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">Processing Speed</td>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">Gradual decline after 40s</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">Working Memory</td>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">Mild decline in early 50s</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">Crystallized Intelligence</td>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">Stable or improving throughout life</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">Executive Functioning</td>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">May show minor decline in late adulthood</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">Emotional Regulation</td>
				<td class="border border-purple-300 px-4 py-2">Improves with age and experience</td>
			  </tr>
			</tbody>
		  </table>

		  <p class="mt-4">
			<strong>Factors Influencing Cognitive Change:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Lifestyle:</strong> Exercise, nutrition, sleep, and mental stimulation matter</li>
			<li><strong>Education:</strong> Higher education correlates with slower cognitive decline</li>
			<li><strong>Health:</strong> Chronic diseases like diabetes and hypertension accelerate cognitive aging</li>
			<li><strong>Social Engagement:</strong> Active social life supports brain health</li>
			<li><strong>Personality:</strong> Openness to experience and conscientiousness protect against decline</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Conclusion:</strong><br>
			Cognitive changes during adulthood are nuanced â€” some aspects decline, others stabilize, and some improve. By adopting healthy habits and engaging actively in life, adults can preserve and enhance cognitive function across the lifespan.
		  </p>

