	  </details>

	  

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-purple-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-purple-800 text-lg">Elucidate the ageing process in late adulthood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-purple-100 border-purple-200">
		  <p>
			Late adulthood, generally defined as age 65 and beyond, marks the final stage of the human lifespan. The ageing process during this period involves gradual physiological decline, cognitive changes, and psychosocial adjustments. While some aspects of aging are universal, individual differences in health, lifestyle, and environment significantly influence the experience.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Physiological Changes:</strong><br>
			Biological aging affects nearly all organ systems. Skin becomes thinner and less elastic, leading to wrinkles and age spots. Muscle mass decreases, bone density declines, and joint flexibility reduces, increasing vulnerability to injury and mobility limitations. Sensory functions also diminish â€” vision (especially near-sightedness and cataracts), hearing (presbycusis), taste, and smell become less acute. Cardiovascular efficiency declines, and metabolic rate slows down, often resulting in weight gain and increased risk of chronic diseases like diabetes and hypertension.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Cognitive Changes:</strong><br>
			Cognitive aging varies widely among individuals. While fluid intelligence (the ability to solve novel problems) tends to decline, crystallized intelligence (accumulated knowledge and verbal skills) often remains stable or even improves. Memory performance, especially short-term and working memory, may show noticeable decline. However, many older adults maintain strong semantic memory and wisdom derived from life experience.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Neurological changes include reduced brain volume, slower neural processing speed, and decreased neurotransmitter production. Despite these changes, the brain retains a degree of plasticity, allowing adaptation and learning throughout life.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Psychosocial Adjustments:</strong><br>
			Psychologically, late adulthood is a time of reflection and re-evaluation. Erik Erikson described the central challenge as <strong>ego integrity vs despair</strong> â€” whether individuals view their lives with satisfaction or regret. Those who feel fulfilled may experience peace and acceptance, while those with unresolved regrets may struggle with depression or existential concerns.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Socially, older adults may experience loss of loved ones, retirement, and changes in living arrangements. These transitions require emotional resilience and support networks. Engagement in meaningful activities, intergenerational relationships, and community involvement can enhance life satisfaction and delay functional decline.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Overall, while aging brings inevitable physical and cognitive changes, maintaining mental engagement, physical activity, social connections, and a positive outlook can significantly enhance quality of life in late adulthood.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
