	  </details>	  


	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-purple-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-purple-800 text-lg">Explain the family cycle approach for adulthood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-purple-100 border-purple-200">
		  <p>
			The family life cycle approach views adult development within the context of family transitions and roles. Each stage of adulthood corresponds to specific family-related milestones, responsibilities, and emotional adaptations.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Stages of the Family Life Cycle:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Young Adulthood:</strong> Establishing independence, exploring relationships, and building a career foundation</li>
			<li><strong>Early Marriage/Partnership:</strong> Learning to navigate shared responsibilities and intimacy</li>
			<li><strong>Childbearing and Raising Young Children:</strong> Balancing parenthood with personal and professional life</li>
			<li><strong>Raising Adolescents:</strong> Managing separation, identity formation, and generational conflict</li>
			<li><strong>Launching Children:</strong> Coping with empty nest, redefining couplehood, and preparing for retirement</li>
			<li><strong>Later Life:</strong> Navigating loss, retirement, and end-of-life transitions</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			<strong>Psychosocial Implications:</strong><br>
			Each stage presents unique challenges and opportunities:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Role Transition:</strong> Shifting from parent to grandparent, worker to retiree, and child to caregiver</li>
			<li><strong>Identity Redefinition:</strong> Letting go of previous roles and embracing new ones</li>
			<li><strong>Emotional Adaptation:</strong> Dealing with grief, loss, and life transitions</li>
			<li><strong>Intergenerational Influence:</strong> Passing down values, traditions, and knowledge</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Application in Counseling and Therapy:</strong><br>
			Therapists use the family life cycle model to understand clientsâ€™ experiences and guide them through transitions. For example:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Helping couples adjust after the birth of a child</li>
			<li>Guiding parents through the empty-nest phase</li>
			<li>Supporting caregivers of elderly relatives</li>
			<li>Facilitating identity shifts during retirement</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			The family life cycle model acknowledges that adult development is deeply intertwined with relational and contextual factors. It emphasizes adaptation, continuity, and interdependence over time.
		  </p>

