	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-teal-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-teal-800 text-lg">Elucidate the family life cycle during adulthood.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-teal-100 border-teal-200">
		  <p>
			The family life cycle describes the predictable stages that families typically pass through, from formation to dissolution or reconfiguration. It provides a framework for understanding how family members adapt emotionally, socially, and psychologically during different life phases.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Key Stages of the Family Life Cycle:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Young Adulthood:</strong> Focus on establishing independence, exploring relationships, and building career foundations</li>
			<li><strong>Marriage/Cohabitation:</strong> Learning to negotiate roles, manage finances, and build emotional intimacy</li>
			<li><strong>Childbearing:</strong> Adapting to parenthood, sleep deprivation, and shifting relationship dynamics</li>
			<li><strong>Raising Young Children:</strong> Balancing work, parenting, and personal needs</li>
			<li><strong>Raising Adolescents:</strong> Managing autonomy, boundary-setting, and emotional distancing</li>
			<li><strong>Launching Children:</strong> Coping with empty nest, redefining couplehood, and supporting adult childrenâ€™s independence</li>
			<li><strong>Retirement and Later Life:</strong> Navigating life without work, facing health issues, and passing on wisdom</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			<strong>Psychosocial Transitions:</strong><br>
			Each stage brings unique developmental tasks and emotional adjustments:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>From Single to Married:</strong> Learning compromise, communication, and shared responsibility</li>
			<li><strong>From Childless to Parent:</strong> Developing patience, prioritization, and nurturance</li>
			<li><strong>From Full Nest to Empty Nest:</strong> Redefining identity beyond parenting</li>
			<li><strong>From Working to Retired:</strong> Finding new sources of meaning and engagement</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Challenges in the Family Life Cycle:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Role strain due to multiple responsibilities</li>
			<li>Conflict over differing life goals among partners</li>
			<li>Generational gaps and parenting styles</li>
			<li>Health and caregiving demands</li>
			<li>Financial and career-related stress</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Resilience and Support Systems:</strong><br>
			Resilience is fostered through:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Strong communication within the family</li>
			<li>Clear boundaries and mutual support</li>
			<li>Open discussions about life changes and expectations</li>
			<li>Access to counseling and support networks</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			The family life cycle is not a rigid sequence but a dynamic process influenced by cultural norms, economic conditions, and personal choices. Understanding this cycle helps individuals anticipate changes and prepare for smooth transitions throughout adulthood.
		  </p>

