	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-orange-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-orange-800 text-lg">Explain the key concepts of Levinson's theory for adult development.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-orange-100 border-orange-200">
		  <p>
			Daniel J. Levinsonâ€™s theory of adult development emphasizes that adult life is composed of alternating <strong>stages of stability</strong> and <strong>transitions</strong>. His model integrates personal, social, and temporal dimensions to explain how individuals construct meaning and identity over time.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Life Structure:</strong><br>
			Levinson introduced the concept of a <strong>life structure</strong> â€” a pattern of roles and relationships that define an individualâ€™s existence. It includes:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Occupational roles</li>
			<li>Relationships (marital, parental, friendships)</li>
			<li>Personal goals and values</li>
			<li>Sociocultural context</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Life structures provide a sense of coherence and purpose. However, they are periodically disrupted by transitions.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Stages of Adult Life:</strong><br>
			Levinson proposed a general sequence of life stages:
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Early Adult Transition (17â€“22):</strong> Leaving the parental world, exploring options, and building a dream</li>
			<li><strong>Entry into Adulthood (22â€“28):</strong> Establishing a life structure, developing relationships, and pursuing career</li>
			<li><strong>Age 30 Transition (28â€“33):</strong> Re-evaluating early adult choices and deciding whether to stay or change course</li>
			<li><strong>Establishment Period (33â€“40):</strong> Consolidating work, love, and friendship roles</li>
			<li><strong>Middle Adult Transition (40â€“45):</strong> Reassessing life structure â€” am I on the right path?</li>
			<li><strong>Midlife Transition (45â€“50):</strong> Confronting mortality, reviewing life, and envisioning the future</li>
			<li><strong>Late Adulthood:</strong> Letting go of youthful dreams and finding peace in lifeâ€™s trajectory</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			<strong>The Dream:</strong><br>
			Central to Levinsonâ€™s theory is the idea of a <strong>dream</strong> â€” an unconscious vision of what one hopes to achieve in life. This dream guides the construction of life structure and evolves with experience.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Transitions:</strong><br>
			Levinson emphasized that transitions are times of re-evaluation, restructuring, and potential upheaval. They involve letting go of the past and embracing a new way of being.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Gender Differences:</strong><br>
			Levinson initially focused on male development but later expanded his model to include women. He acknowledged that women often experience more complex transitions due to dual roles in work and family.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Applications:</strong><br>
			Levinsonâ€™s theory is used in life coaching, therapy, and career counseling to help adults:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Reflect on life choices</li>
			<li>Manage career and relationship transitions</li>
			<li>Re-evaluate life goals and redefine success</li>
			<li>Understand midlife crises as normal parts of development</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			In summary, Levinsonâ€™s theory provides a roadmap of adult development, emphasizing the interplay between personal dreams, life structures, and transitional periods. It offers a compelling lens for understanding how adults grow, change, and evolve across the lifespan.
		  </p>

