	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-green-800 text-lg">Describe development during adult years. Compare the stage theories and the contextual approach to development during this period.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-green-100 border-green-200">
		  <p>
			Adult development involves profound psychological, emotional, and social transformations. From young adulthood to late maturity, individuals navigate identity, relationships, work, and meaning-making.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Stage Theories:</strong><br>
			Stage-based models describe adult development as a series of predictable phases:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Erik Erikson:</strong> Proposes psychosocial stages such as intimacy vs isolation and generativity vs stagnation</li>
			<li><strong>Daniel Levinson:</strong> Describes life structures and transitions, including early adulthood (ages 22â€“28), midlife crisis (40â€“45), and late adulthood</li>
			<li><strong>Kohlbergâ€™s Moral Development:</strong> Expands into postconventional morality in adulthood</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			These theories suggest that all individuals follow a similar trajectory, facing key developmental tasks at specific ages.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Contextual Approach:</strong><br>
			In contrast, the contextual approach views adult development as fluid and influenced by external forces:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Career opportunities and economic stability</li>
			<li>Family dynamics and role changes</li>
			<li>Health and lifestyle choices</li>
			<li>Cultural expectations and gender roles</li>
			<li>Personal values and life goals</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Contextual models emphasize that there is no single "correct" path through adulthood. People construct meaning based on lived experience, not just internal maturation.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Comparative Insights:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <p>
			- <strong>Stage Theories</strong> offer clarity and predictability, helping professionals understand broad developmental themes<br>
			- <strong>Contextual Approaches</strong> provide deeper insight into individual differences, highlighting how personal history, culture, and environment influence growth
		  </p>

		  <p>
			For example, a person in middle adulthood might experience a sense of generativity if they're raising children and mentoring others. However, another individual in the same age range who is child-free or self-employed may define generativity very differently â€” perhaps through creative output or community service.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Similarly, midlife transitions may involve career shifts for some and spiritual exploration for others, depending on life circumstances and cultural expectations.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Conclusion:</strong><br>
			Both models contribute valuable insights. Stage theories help identify common themes and milestones, while contextual models allow for personalized interpretations and interventions.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
