	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-indigo-800 text-lg">Discuss the development during adult years in terms of stage vs contextual theories.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-indigo-100 border-indigo-200">
		  <p>
			Adult development can be understood through two major theoretical lenses: <strong>stage theories</strong> and <strong>contextual theories</strong>. Each offers a different perspective on how people grow and change in adulthood.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Stage Theories:</strong><br>
			Stage theories propose that development unfolds in a series of discrete phases, each with its own psychological task or crisis. These include:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Eriksonâ€™s Stages:</strong> Intimacy vs isolation, generativity vs stagnation, ego integrity vs despair</li>
			<li><strong>Levinsonâ€™s Life Structure Model:</strong> Entry into adulthood, midlife transition, settling down phase</li>
			<li><strong>Havighurstâ€™s Developmental Tasks:</strong> Achieving civic and social responsibility, maintaining health, adapting to aging</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			These theories assume that adults face similar challenges at certain ages and must resolve them to progress psychologically.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Contextual Theories:</strong><br>
			Contextual theories argue that adult development is shaped by:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Historical and cultural background</li>
			<li>Personal life events and decisions</li>
			<li>Work and family roles</li>
			<li>Access to resources and opportunities</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Unlike stage theories, the contextual approach sees development as non-linear and highly variable. There is no single â€œrightâ€ way to develop; instead, individuals adapt to changing environments and life circumstances.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Examples of Contextual Influences:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>A person raised in a collectivist culture may prioritize family over individual achievement</li>
			<li>Someone affected by economic downturn may delay retirement or career advancement</li>
			<li>Women may experience different developmental paths due to dual roles in family and work</li>
			<li>Individuals in rapidly changing fields may go through repeated relearning and adaptation</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Integration of Theories:</strong><br>
			Modern developmental psychology often combines both views:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Stage theories provide a scaffold for understanding common transitions</li>
			<li>Contextual models explain why some individuals deviate from expected paths</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			This integrated approach allows researchers and practitioners to recognize developmental milestones while respecting individual variation.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Conclusion:</strong><br>
			Stage theories offer a structured view of adult development, emphasizing universal patterns and psychological tasks. Contextual theories highlight the importance of life context, flexibility, and sociocultural influences.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Together, these perspectives offer a comprehensive understanding of adult growth â€” one that balances theory with lived experience.
		  </p>

