	<!-- Question Card: Cognitive Development Theories -->
	<div class="question-card bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-xl border border-blue-200">
	  <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700 mb-5 flex items-center">
		<span class="mr-2">ðŸ”¹</span> COGNITIVE DEVELOPMENT THEORIES
	  </h3>
	
	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-indigo-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-indigo-800 text-lg">Explain Piagetâ€™s idea on decentration and conservation tasks.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-indigo-100 border-indigo-200">
		  <p>
			Jean Piaget, a pioneering developmental psychologist, proposed that children progress through distinct stages of cognitive development. Two key concepts from his preoperational and concrete operational stages are <strong>decentration</strong> and <strong>conservation</strong>, both of which reflect the child's growing ability to think logically and consider multiple aspects of a situation simultaneously.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Decentration:</strong><br>
			Decentration refers to the ability to shift attention between different features or dimensions of an object or situation. Young children in the preoperational stage (ages 2â€“7) tend to be <em>centered</em> â€” meaning they focus on only one salient aspect of a stimulus while ignoring others. For example, a child may believe a tall glass holds more water than a short, wide glass simply because it looks taller. As children mature and enter the concrete operational stage (ages 7â€“11), they develop the capacity to decenter â€” considering multiple attributes (e.g., height and width) and recognizing that changes in one dimension do not necessarily mean a change in quantity.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Conservation:</strong><br>
			Conservation is the understanding that certain properties (like mass, volume, number, or length) remain constant despite changes in appearance. Piaget demonstrated this through classic experiments involving liquids, clay, and counters. For instance, when equal amounts of water are poured into differently shaped containers, pre-conservers (younger children) often say the amount has changed based on the container's shape. Older children who have developed conservation understand that the actual quantity remains unchanged.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			These abilities â€” decentration and conservation â€” mark important milestones in cognitive development. They indicate that children are beginning to apply logical reasoning and reversibility (the ability to mentally reverse an action), which are hallmarks of operational thought. These skills lay the foundation for more advanced mathematical and scientific reasoning in later years.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Educators and caregivers can support the development of these abilities by providing hands-on experiences, encouraging children to compare and contrast objects, and asking open-ended questions that promote flexible thinking and perspective-taking.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>

	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-orange-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-orange-800 text-lg">Elucidate Piagetâ€™s idea on decentration and conservation tasks.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-orange-100 border-orange-200">
		  <p>
			Jean Piagetâ€™s research on cognitive development introduced two key concepts: <strong>decentration</strong> and <strong>conservation</strong>. These emerged during the <strong>concrete operational stage</strong> (ages 7â€“11) and marked a significant departure from earlier egocentric thinking.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Decentration:</strong><br>
			Before this stage, children tend to be <em>centered</em> â€” meaning they focus on only one aspect of a situation at a time. For example, a child might say a tall glass holds more water than a short one, even if both contain the same amount.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			With decentration, children begin to attend to multiple dimensions simultaneously. They can consider both height and width when judging volume, or both effort and outcome when assessing fairness.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			This ability is central to logical thinking and problem-solving. It allows children to coordinate different features of a task, leading to more mature reasoning.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Conservation:</strong><br>
			Conservation refers to the understanding that certain properties remain constant despite changes in appearance. Classic conservation tasks involve quantity, number, mass, length, and volume.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In a typical experiment, children are shown two identical glasses of water. When one is poured into a taller, narrower glass, pre-conservers (younger children) believe the amount has changed, while conservers (older children) understand it hasnâ€™t.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Conservation depends on the childâ€™s ability to reverse mental operations â€” to imagine pouring the water back and restoring the original state. It also relies on decentration, as the child must consider both shape and volume together.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Developmental Significance:</strong><br>
			These abilities signal the childâ€™s movement from preoperational to concrete operational thinking. They indicate:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Logical reasoning</li>
			<li>Decontextualized thinking</li>
			<li>Ability to conserve and transform mental images</li>
			<li>Emerging understanding of invariance and reversibility</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			These cognitive milestones enable children to solve problems systematically and understand that appearances can be misleading.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Classroom Application:</strong><br>
			Teachers can facilitate the development of decentration and conservation through hands-on activities, manipulatives, and guided discovery. Encouraging children to explain their reasoning fosters deeper understanding.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			In sum, decentration and conservation represent major leaps in cognitive maturity. They lay the groundwork for more advanced reasoning in later stages of development.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>


	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-red-800 text-lg">Explain Kohlberg's theory of moral development.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-red-100 border-red-200">
		  <p>
			Lawrence Kohlberg expanded upon Jean Piagetâ€™s work and proposed a comprehensive theory of moral development that spans childhood, adolescence, and adulthood. His theory is based on the idea that moral reasoning develops through a series of hierarchical stages tied to increasing cognitive maturity.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Kohlbergâ€™s Six Stages of Moral Development:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Stage 1: Obedience and Punishment Orientation</strong><br>
			  Children view rules as absolute and unchangeable. The primary motivation is to avoid punishment.</li>

			<li><strong>Stage 2: Individualism and Exchange</strong><br>
			  Children recognize that different perspectives exist. They begin to think about what benefits them personally.</li>

			<li><strong>Stage 3: Good Interpersonal Relationships</strong><br>
			  Adolescents make decisions based on living up to expectations of others and maintaining relationships.</li>

			<li><strong>Stage 4: Maintaining Social Order</strong><br>
			  Individuals begin to consider laws and societal norms when making moral judgments.</li>

			<li><strong>Stage 5: Social Contract and Individual Rights</strong><br>
			  People understand that laws can be modified to serve society better. Justice and rights become central concerns.</li>

			<li><strong>Stage 6: Universal Ethical Principles</strong><br>
			  Rarely achieved, this stage involves decisions based on self-chosen ethical principles such as equality, dignity, and human rights.</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			<strong>Level 1 â€“ Preconventional Morality:</strong><br>
			At this level, children rely on external consequences to determine right and wrong. Their moral thinking is egocentric and rule-bound.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Level 2 â€“ Conventional Morality:</strong><br>
			Children and adolescents now internalize social norms and strive to meet expectations. They value conformity, loyalty, and social harmony.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Level 3 â€“ Postconventional Morality:</strong><br>
			This level represents advanced moral reasoning. It emphasizes universal principles, personal ethics, and critical reflection on societal norms.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Educational Implications:</strong><br>
			Kohlbergâ€™s theory has been applied in classrooms to promote moral discussion and critical thinking. Teachers use moral dilemmas to encourage students to reflect on justice, fairness, and empathy.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Criticisms:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Gender bias â€“ most examples are drawn from boysâ€™ responses</li>
			<li>Not all individuals reach Stage 5 or 6</li>
			<li>Some argue that moral behavior does not always match moral reasoning</li>
			<li>Underestimates the role of emotions, culture, and relationships</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Despite these criticisms, Kohlbergâ€™s theory remains influential in developmental psychology. It provides a framework for understanding how moral reasoning becomes increasingly complex with age and exposure to diverse experiences.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>

	  
	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-blue-800 text-lg">Compare Piagetâ€™s and Kohlbergâ€™s theories of moral development.</summary>
		<div class="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-blue-100 border-blue-200">
		  <p>
			Jean Piaget and Lawrence Kohlberg both proposed stage-based theories of moral development, but they differ in scope, methodology, and emphasis. Both viewed moral reasoning as a developmental process, yet their models diverge significantly in complexity and application.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Piagetâ€™s Theory:</strong><br>
			Piaget was one of the first to study children's moral reasoning systematically. He identified two major stages of moral development:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Heteronomous Morality (ages 4â€“7):</strong> Children view rules as fixed and handed down by authority figures. They judge actions based on consequences rather than intentions.</li>
			<li><strong>Autonomous Morality (ages 8+):</strong> Children begin to understand that rules can be negotiated and are based on mutual respect. Intentions become more important than outcomes.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Piaget emphasized peer interaction as the key driver of moral growth, arguing that it promotes perspective-taking and cooperation. His research focused primarily on school-age children and used storytelling to explore how children judged moral dilemmas.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Kohlbergâ€™s Theory:</strong><br>
			Building on Piagetâ€™s work, Kohlberg expanded moral development into adolescence and adulthood. He proposed six stages grouped into three levels:
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Preconventional Level:</strong> Moral reasoning is based on avoiding punishment and gaining rewards.</li>
			<li><strong>Conventional Level:</strong> Emphasis on social approval and maintaining social order.</li>
			<li><strong>Postconventional Level:</strong> Focus shifts to individual rights, justice, and ethical principles.</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			Kohlberg believed moral development continues throughout life and involves increasingly complex reasoning about justice, rights, and societal laws.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Key Similarities:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Both propose stage-based development of moral reasoning.</li>
			<li>Moral growth occurs through cognitive maturation and social experience.</li>
			<li>Peer interaction plays a crucial role in advancing moral understanding.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Key Differences:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <table class="w-full table-auto mt-4 border-collapse border border-gray-300">
			<thead>
			  <tr class="bg-blue-200">
				<th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Aspect</th>
				<th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Piaget</th>
				<th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Kohlberg</th>
			  </tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Stages</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">2 stages</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">6 stages across 3 levels</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Focus Age Group</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Children up to age 10</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">All ages, including adults</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Moral Judgment Basis</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Intentions vs consequences</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Justice, rights, and ethics</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Methodology</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Observational studies and stories</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Hypothetical dilemmas and interviews</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Developmental Continuity</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Believed morality matures early</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Believed moral reasoning evolves lifelong</td>
			  </tr>
			</tbody>
		  </table>

		  <p class="mt-4">
			<strong>Critiques:</strong><br>
			Piagetâ€™s model has been criticized for being too simplistic and limited to younger children. Kohlbergâ€™s theory has been accused of gender bias (focused on male moral reasoning) and cultural insensitivity â€” emphasizing Western ideals of justice over care or community values.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Despite differences, both theories contributed significantly to understanding how individuals develop moral reasoning over time, and how this reflects broader cognitive and emotional maturity.
		  </p>

		  <button class="copy-btn mt-4 px-5 py-2 flex items-center justify-center space-x-2 text-white rounded-md focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-emerald-500 focus:ring-opacity-50"
				  onclick="copyToClipboard(this.previousElementSibling.textContent)">
			<span>Copy Answer</span>
			<span class="text-xl">ðŸ“‹</span>
		  </button>
		</div>
	  </details>


	  <details class="mb-4 p-4 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
		<summary class="font-medium text-blue-800 text-lg">Compare Piaget's and Kohlberg's theories of moral development during school years.</summary>
		<div class of="mt-4 p-4 rounded-md border answer-box-content bg-blue-100 border-blue-200">
		  <p>
			Jean Piaget and Lawrence Kohlberg both made significant contributions to understanding moral development in children. While they share some foundational ideas, their theories differ in scope, methodology, and complexity.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Piagetâ€™s Theory:</strong><br>
			Piaget studied how children reason about rules, justice, and fairness. He proposed two major stages:
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Heteronomous Morality (ages 4â€“7):</strong> Children see rules as fixed and handed down by authority figures. They judge actions based on consequences rather than intentions.</li>
			<li><strong>Autonomous Morality (ages 8+):</strong> Children begin to understand that rules can be negotiated and changed through mutual agreement. Intentions become more important than outcomes.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			Piaget emphasized peer interaction as a key driver of moral growth. Through games and group activities, children learn cooperation, fairness, and reciprocity.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			His research methods included storytelling and observing how children judged moral dilemmas. For example, he found that younger children focused on the amount of damage done, while older children considered intent.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Kohlbergâ€™s Theory:</strong><br>
			Building on Piagetâ€™s foundation, Kohlberg expanded moral development into adolescence and adulthood. He proposed six stages grouped into three levels:
		  </p>

		  <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 mb-4">
			<li><strong>Preconventional Level:</strong> Moral reasoning is based on avoiding punishment and gaining rewards.</li>
			<li><strong>Conventional Level:</strong> Emphasis shifts to social approval and maintaining societal order.</li>
			<li><strong>Postconventional Level:</strong> Focus moves toward individual rights, ethical principles, and social contracts.</li>
		  </ol>

		  <p>
			Kohlberg believed moral development continues throughout life and used hypothetical dilemmas â€” like the famous â€œHeinz dilemmaâ€ â€” to explore how people reason about right and wrong.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			<strong>Key Similarities:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
			<li>Both propose stage-based development of moral reasoning.</li>
			<li>Moral growth occurs through cognitive maturation and social experience.</li>
			<li>Peer interaction plays a crucial role in advancing moral judgment.</li>
		  </ul>

		  <p>
			<strong>Key Differences:</strong>
		  </p>

		  <table class="w-full table-auto mt-4 border-collapse border border-gray-300">
			<thead>
			  <tr class="bg-blue-200">
				<th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Aspect</th>
				<th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Piaget</th>
				<th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 text-left">Kohlberg</th>
			  </tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Stages</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">2 stages</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">6 stages across 3 levels</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Focus Age Group</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Children up to age 10</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">All ages, including adults</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Moral Judgment Basis</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Intentions vs consequences</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Justice, rights, and ethics</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Methodology</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Observational studies and stories</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Hypothetical dilemmas and interviews</td>
			  </tr>
			  <tr>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Developmental Continuity</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Believed morality matures early</td>
				<td class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2">Believed moral reasoning evolves lifelong</td>
			  </tr>
			</tbody>
		  </table>

		  <p class="mt-4">
			<strong>Critiques:</strong><br>
			- Piagetâ€™s model has been criticized for being too simplistic and limited to younger children.<br>
			- Kohlbergâ€™s theory has been accused of gender bias (focused on male moral reasoning) and cultural insensitivity â€” emphasizing Western ideals of justice over care or community values.
		  </p>

		  <p>
			Despite differences, both theories contributed significantly to understanding how individuals develop moral reasoning over time, and how this reflects broader cognitive and emotional maturity.
		  </p>

